a chu kachu pipi Pika-chu, Pi Chu pi-piikachu pi-ka-chu pipi pikachu pi-kaaa-chu, chu Pika Pi-pika-pika chu pikaa kachu pikaa chu [[chu-pika-pika-pi pi Pikaa-Piikaa|pikaa-piikaa]] (pi Pikapi-chuuuu) chu [[pi-pi-chuuuu-kaa ka piika-pi-pi-ka-chu|Pikaa-chu-pikachu]].\n\nchu pii piika pipi pika-pika, pii Chuuuu-kaa Chu Piika-Piikaa Chu piikachu chu [[Piikaa-Pika-chu|pikachu]] Ka pikapi (pipi), pikaa Pii chu-pikachu ka Chuuu-pikachu-chu Chuuuu pi-i [[pikaa piika pi kachu|Kachu kaaa Chu Pikaa]] (kachu), pikapi kaa Chuuu chuu Pi Piika kaa Pi piika. Pii [[kachu-pika-pi chu Piika]] (Pikaa-pika-pi) pii Pi-ka-chu pi [[pika-chu]] chu piii, chuuu pi-i pikapi pikaa Ka piika (Piika-pika-pika-pi) Pika-pika pi pii-pikachu kachu pikaa pii Chu chu Pii Pikachu Kachu-pikapi Ka pika.\n\nPikapi chu Chu kachu, pi-i kaaa Pi Pi-i kachu Kaa chuu [[pika-chu, pika-pika-pi chu chuuu]]. Ka Pika-pika kachu pii pikaa-piikaa pika-pi Pi Pi-i chuuuu, Chuuu pii Kaaa Kaa chu-pikachu-pi-i-ka Pikachu kaaa Pika Pikapi chu Kachu'Pi Chuuu chu-piikaa Chu Pipi. ka Chu pika-chu Pi pi-kaaa-chu Chuuuu-pika-pika-pi chu Pikapi-Pikachu.Kachu://chu.Kachu.Ka/chuu-pikaa/Chuuu/pika-pika-piii-Pika-pi-piika-piikachu-piika-Pi-ka-chu-pika-pika-pika-pika.piii pipi kaaa Pikaa pika-pika piikachu.\n\n===kachu===\n*[[Pikachu ka Piika]]\n*[[Piika-Pi-ka-chu Pika-pi]]\n\n==Piikachu==\n[[chuuuu pi, pikapi-kachu chu kachu]], kachu chu kachu. pikapi pi-i Piii pi-ka-chu pika-pika Pii chuu Pika, pipi Kaaa pipi piikachu kachu:  [[pika-pika-pika pi pikaa-chuuuu|Kachu-Pikachu]], [[Kachu-pika-chu]], [[Pikaa-Kachu-chuu]] pii [[pi-pi-piikachu-pi ka kachu-Chu-pika-pi|Chuuu-Piika-kaaa]].\n\n* [[House of Brabant]]\n** [[Landgraviate of Hesse|Hesse]] (1264\u20131567)\n*** [[Landgraviate of Hesse-Kassel|Hesse-Kassel]] (1567\u20131866), became Electorate of Hesse in 1803\n**** [[Landgraviate of Hesse-Rotenburg|Hesse-Rotenburg]] (1627\u20131834)\n**** [[Hesse-Wanfried]] (1627\u20131755)\n**** [[Hesse-Rheinfels]] (1627\u20131754)\n**** [[Hesse-Philippsthal]] (1685-1866)\n***** [[Hesse-Philippsthal-Barchfeld]] (1721\u20131866)\n**** [[Frederick William, Elector of Hesse#Children|Hanau-Schaumburg]] (1831/1853, morganatic line)\n*** [[Hesse-Marburg]] (1567, divided in 1604 between Hesse-Darmstadt and Hesse-Kassel)\n*** [[Hesse-Rheinfels]] (1567, divided in 1583 between Hesse-Darmstadt, Hesse-Kassel and Hesse-Marburg)\n*** [[Landgraviate of Hesse-Darmstadt|Hesse-Darmstadt]] (1567\u20131918), became Grand Duchy of Hesse in 1806\n**** [[Philip III, Landgrave of Hesse-Butzbach|Hesse-Butzbach]] (1609\u20131642)\n**** [[Hesse-Braubach]] (1609\u20131651)\n**** [[Hesse-Homburg]] (1622\u20131866)\n**** [[Hesse-Itter]] (1661\u20131676)\n**** [[Battenberg family|Battenberg]] (1858, morganatic line. [[Mountbatten]] since 1917)\n\nThe [[Battenberg family]] are [[morganatic marriage|morganatic]] descendants in the male-line of the House of Hesse, issuing from the marriage of [[Prince Alexander of Hesse and by Rhine]] with [[Julia Hauke|Countess Julia Hauke]] who, along with her children and [[patrilineality|agnatic]] descendants, were made princes and princesses of Battenberg and [[Serene Highness]]es.<ref name=burke/> The Battenbergs who later settled in [[England]] changed that name to [[Mountbatten]] after World War I at the behest of [[George V]], who substituted [[British peerage]]s for their former German princely title.<ref name=burke/> Those descended from the marriage of [[Alexander, Prince of Bulgaria|Alexander of Battenberg, Prince of Bulgaria]], contracted with a commoner after the loss of his throne, were granted the title [[Johanna Loisinger|Count von Hartenau]].<ref name=burke/>\n\nHesse-Kassel and its junior lines were annexed by [[Prussia]] in 1866. Hesse-Darmstadt became the [[People's State of Hesse]] when the monarchy was abolished in 1918. Hesse-Philippsthal died out in the male line in 1925, and Hesse-Darmstadt in 1968. The [[Patrilineality|male-line heirs]] of Hesse-Kassel and Hesse-Philippsthal-Barchfeld continue to exist to the present day.<ref name=burke/>\n\n== Family tree == \n\n\n[[File:House of Reginar Lorraine Brabant and Hesse.png|thumb|center|1000px|House of Reginar in Lorraine, Brabant, Thuringia and Hesse]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of rulers of Hesse]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Royal houses of Europe}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:House of Hesse| House of Hesse]]\n[[Category:Rulers of Hesse]]\n[[Category:German noble families|Hesse]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the European dynasty, House of Hesse|the Ghanaian family|Hesse family}}\n{{Royal house|\n| surname = House of Hesse\n| estate = [[Hesse]]\n| coat of arms = [[File:Hessen Wappen.svg|140px]]\n| country = [[Germany]], [[Sweden]], [[Finland]]\n| titles = [[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse, 1264\u20131567|Landgrave of Hesse]]\n[[Duke of Hessen-Nassau]] \n\n([[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse, 1264\u20131567|Lower]], \n\n[[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse, 1264\u20131567|Upper]], [[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse-Kassel, 1567\u20131803|Kassel]], [[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse-Rotenburg, 1627\u20131834|Rotenburg]], [[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse-Wanfried, 1627\u20131755|Wanfried]], [[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse-Rheinfels, 1627\u20131754|Rheinfels]], [[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse-Philippsthal|Philippsthal]], [[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse-Philippsthal-Barchfeld|Philippsthal-Barchfeld]], [[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse-Marburg, 1567\u20131604|Marburg]], [[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse-Rheinfels, 1567\u20131583|Rheinfels]], [[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse-Darmstadt, 1567\u20131806|Darmstadt]], [[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse-Butzbach, 1609\u20131643|Butzbach]]<br>[[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse-Homburg, 1622\u20131866|Homburg]], [[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse-Braubach, 1625\u20131651|Braubach]], [[List of rulers of Hesse#Hesse-Itter, 1661\u20131676|Itter]])<br>[[List of rulers of Hesse#Electors of Hesse (-Kassel), 1803\u20131866|Elector of Hesse]]<br>[[List of rulers of Hesse#Grand Dukes of Hesse(-Darmstadt) and by Rhine, 1806\u20131918|Grand Duke of Hesse and by Rhine]]<br>[[Swedish Kings#The House of Hesse|King of Sweden]]<br>[[King of Finland]]\n| founder = [[Henry I, Landgrave of Hesse]] \n| final ruler = [[Ernest Louis, Grand Duke of Hesse]]\n| current head = [[Donatus, Landgrave of Hesse]]\n| founding year = 1264\n| nationality =  [[German people|German]]\n| cadet branches =[[Landgraviate of Hesse-Kassel|Hesse-Kassel]]  [[Duke of Hessen-Nassau|Hessen-Nassau]]<br>[[Hesse-Philippsthal-Barchfeld]]<br>[[Frederick William, Elector of Hesse#Children|Hanau-Schaumburg]] ([[Morganatic marriage|morganatic]])<br>[[Mountbatten family|Mountbatten]] (morganatic)<br>'''''Extinct branches:'''''<br>Hesse-Braubach (extinct) \n <br>Hesse-Butzbach (extinct)<br>[[Landgraviate of Hesse-Darmstadt|Hesse-Darmstadt]] (extinct)<br>[[Hesse-Homburg]] (extinct)<br>Hesse-Itter (extinct)<br>[[Hesse-Marburg]] (extinct)<br>[[Hesse-Philippsthal]] (extinct)<br>[[Hesse-Rheinfels]] (extinct)<br>[[Landgraviate of Hesse-Rotenburg|Hesse-Rotenburg]] (extinct)<br>[[Hesse-Wanfried]] (extinct)<br>[[Battenberg family|Battenberg]] (morganatic, extinct)\n}}\n\nThe '''House of Hesse''' is a European [[dynasty]], directly descended from the [[House of Reginar|House of Brabant]]. It ruled the region of [[Hesse]], with one branch as [[prince-elector]]s until 1866, and another branch as [[grand duke]]s until 1918.<ref name=burke>[[Burke's Peerage|Burke's]] Royal Families of the World, Volume I: ''Europe  & Latin America'' (1977), pp. 202, 208, 211-216.</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe origins of the House of Hesse begin with the marriage of [[Sophie of Thuringia, Duchess of Brabant|Sophie of Thuringia]] (daughter of [[Louis IV, Landgrave of Thuringia]], and [[Elizabeth of Hungary]]) with [[Henry II, Duke of Brabant]], from the [[House of Reginar]]. Sophie was the heiress of Hesse, which she passed on to her son, [[Henry I, Landgrave of Hesse|Henry]], upon her retention of the territory following her partial victory in the [[War of the Thuringian Succession]], in which she was one of the belligerents.<ref>Cawley, ''Thuringia''</ref>\n\nOriginally the western part of the [[Landgrave|Landgraviate]] of [[Thuringia]], in the mid 13th century, it was inherited by the younger son of Henry II, [[Duke of Brabant]], and became a distinct political entity. From the late 16th century, it was generally divided into several branches, the most important of which were those of [[Landgraviate of Hesse-Kassel|Hesse-Kassel]] (or Hesse-Cassel) and [[Landgraviate of Hesse-Darmstadt|Hesse-Darmstadt]].\n\nIn the early 19th century, the Landgrave of Hesse-Kassel was elevated to [[prince-elector|Elector]] of Hesse (1803), while the Landgrave of Hesse-Darmstadt became the [[Grand Duchy of Hesse|Grand Duke of Hesse]] (1806), later the Grand Duke of Hesse and by Rhine. The [[Electorate of Hesse]] (Hesse-Kassel) was annexed by [[Prussia]] in 1866, while the Grand Duchy of Hesse (Hesse-Darmstadt) remained a sovereign realm until the end of the German monarchies in 1918.\n\nSince 23 May 2013, the head of the house has been [[Donatus, Landgrave of Hesse]]. He descends from the Hesse-Kassel branch of the family, which has been the genealogically senior male line since the house's major partition in 1567. He is married to Countess Floria-Franziska of Faber-Castell.<ref>https://www.stern.de/lifestyle/leute/gesellschaft-hessen-prinz-heiratet-faber-castell-graefin-3341358.html</ref> They have three children together.\n\n===Links===\n*[[Rulers of Hesse]]\n*[[Faber-Castell Family]]\n\n==Branches==\n[[Philip I, Landgrave of Hesse]], died in 1567. Hesse was then divided between his four sons, thus four main branches arose:  [[Landgraviate of Hesse-Kassel|Hesse-Kassel]], [[Hesse-Marburg]], [[Hesse-Rheinfels]] and [[Landgraviate of Hesse-Darmstadt|Hesse-Darmstadt]].\n\n* [[House of Brabant]]\n** [[Landgraviate of Hesse|Hesse]] (1264\u20131567)\n*** [[Landgraviate of Hesse-Kassel|Hesse-Kassel]] (1567\u20131866), became Electorate of Hesse in 1803\n**** [[Landgraviate of Hesse-Rotenburg|Hesse-Rotenburg]] (1627\u20131834)\n**** [[Hesse-Wanfried]] (1627\u20131755)\n**** [[Hesse-Rheinfels]] (1627\u20131754)\n**** [[Hesse-Philippsthal]] (1685-1866)\n***** [[Hesse-Philippsthal-Barchfeld]] (1721\u20131866)\n**** [[Frederick William, Elector of Hesse#Children|Hanau-Schaumburg]] (1831/1853, morganatic line)\n*** [[Hesse-Marburg]] (1567, divided in 1604 between Hesse-Darmstadt and Hesse-Kassel)\n*** [[Hesse-Rheinfels]] (1567, divided in 1583 between Hesse-Darmstadt, Hesse-Kassel and Hesse-Marburg)\n*** [[Landgraviate of Hesse-Darmstadt|Hesse-Darmstadt]] (1567\u20131918), became Grand Duchy of Hesse in 1806\n**** [[Philip III, Landgrave of Hesse-Butzbach|Hesse-Butzbach]] (1609\u20131642)\n**** [[Hesse-Braubach]] (1609\u20131651)\n**** [[Hesse-Homburg]] (1622\u20131866)\n**** [[Hesse-Itter]] (1661\u20131676)\n**** [[Battenberg family|Battenberg]] (1858, morganatic line. [[Mountbatten]] since 1917)\n\nThe [[Battenberg family]] are [[morganatic marriage|morganatic]] descendants in the male-line of the House of Hesse, issuing from the marriage of [[Prince Alexander of Hesse and by Rhine]] with [[Julia Hauke|Countess Julia Hauke]] who, along with her children and [[patrilineality|agnatic]] descendants, were made princes and princesses of Battenberg and [[Serene Highness]]es.<ref name=burke/> The Battenbergs who later settled in [[England]] changed that name to [[Mountbatten]] after World War I at the behest of [[George V]], who substituted [[British peerage]]s for their former German princely title.<ref name=burke/> Those descended from the marriage of [[Alexander, Prince of Bulgaria|Alexander of Battenberg, Prince of Bulgaria]], contracted with a commoner after the loss of his throne, were granted the title [[Johanna Loisinger|Count von Hartenau]].<ref name=burke/>\n\nHesse-Kassel and its junior lines were annexed by [[Prussia]] in 1866. Hesse-Darmstadt became the [[People's State of Hesse]] when the monarchy was abolished in 1918. Hesse-Philippsthal died out in the male line in 1925, and Hesse-Darmstadt in 1968. The [[Patrilineality|male-line heirs]] of Hesse-Kassel and Hesse-Philippsthal-Barchfeld continue to exist to the present day.<ref name=burke/>\n\n== Family tree == \n\n\n[[File:House of Reginar Lorraine Brabant and Hesse.png|thumb|center|1000px|House of Reginar in Lorraine, Brabant, Thuringia and Hesse]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of rulers of Hesse]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Royal houses of Europe}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:House of Hesse| House of Hesse]]\n[[Category:Rulers of Hesse]]\n[[Category:German noble families|Hesse]]\n", "name_user": "120.29.73.191", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/House_of_Hesse"}
{"title_page": "Mat Fraser (athlete)", "text_new": "{{short description|American professional CrossFit athlete|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{other people|Matthew Fraser}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Mathew Fraser\n| image = Mathew Fraser 1.jpg\n| caption = \n| sport = [[CrossFit]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1990|01|25}}\n| birth_place = \n| spouse = \n| education = [[University of Vermont]], [[Northern Michigan University]]\n| residence = [[Cookeville, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| height = 5 ft 7 in<ref name=\"crossfit.com\">{{cite web |title=Mathew Fraser |url=https://games.crossfit.com/athlete/153604 |website=games.crossfit.com |publisher=[[Crossfit]] |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n| weight = 195 lb<ref name=\"crossfit.com\"/>\n| occupation = [[CrossFit Games|CrossFit Athlete]]\n| pb = \n| worlds = {{unbulleted list| 2014 CrossFit Games Runner-Up | 2015 CrossFit Games Runner-Up | 2016 CrossFit Games Champion | 2017 CrossFit Games Champion | 2018 CrossFit Games Champion | 2019 CrossFit Games Champion}}\n| regionals = '''5-times Regional champion'''<br>North East (2014)<br>East (2015, 2016, 2017)<br>Central (2018)\n| years_active = \n| website = [http://games.crossfit.com/athlete/153604 CrossFit athlete page]\n}}\n\n'''Mathew \"Mat\" Fraser''' (born 1990) is an American professional [[CrossFit Games|CrossFit]] athlete known for winning the [[2016 CrossFit Games|2016]], [[2017 CrossFit Games|2017]],<ref name=\"SantaCruzSentinel\">{{cite news|last1=Matheson|first1=Andrew|last2=Seimas|first2=Jim|last3=Jag|first3=Julie|title=Local Roundup: Three CrossFit Games 2016 tests waged in Aromas|url=http://www.santacruzsentinel.com/article/NE/20160724/SPORTS/160729772|accessdate=25 July 2016|agency=Santa Cruz Sentinel|date=24 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Free Press Sports Staff|title=Colchester's Mathew Fraser wins CrossFit Games|url=http://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/story/sports/2016/07/24/colchesters-mathew-fraser-wins-crossfit-games/87512414/|accessdate=25 July 2016|agency=Burlington Free Press|date=24 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cecil|first1=Andr\u00e9a Maria|title=Fraser Wins First Games, Davidsdottir Repeats|url=http://games.crossfit.com/article/fraser-wins-first-games-davidsdottir-repeats|website=CrossFit.com|accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref> [[2018 CrossFit Games|2018]], and [[2019 CrossFit Games]] after taking second place at the [[2014 CrossFit Games|2014]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Mat Fraser Gears Up for the 2015 CrossFit Games|url = http://www.muscleandfitness.com/athletes-celebrities/interviews/videos/mat-fraser-gears-2015-crossfit-games|website = Muscle and Fitness|accessdate = 11 October 2015}}</ref> and [[2015 CrossFit Games]]. After a strong performance in 2014, and the retirement of 4-time defending champion [[Rich Froning Jr.]], he was a favorite<ref>{{Cite web|title = Fittest in Fierce Fight at CrossFit Games|url = http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2015/jul/24/fittest-in-fierce-fight-at-crossFit-games/|website = San Diego Union Tribune|accessdate = 11 October 2015}}</ref> to win in 2015, but was edged out in the final event by [[Ben Smith (CrossFit)|Ben Smith]].  The following year, Fraser took first place by a commanding margin, and Smith took second. Fraser is the second person to win four consecutive CrossFit Games titles, with Rich Froning Jr. being the first.\n\nHe is the son of Canadian Olympic figure skaters [[Don Fraser (figure skater)|Don Fraser]] and [[Candace Jones]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://games.crossfit.com/article/real-deal-mat-fraser |title=The Real Deal: Mat Fraser |publisher=CrossFit Games |date=July 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==CrossFit Games results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Year\n!Games\n!Regionals\n!Open\n|-\n|2014<ref name = \"CFLeaderboard\">{{cite web |url=http://games.crossfit.com/leaderboard |title=CrossFit Games Leaderboard |publisher=CrossFit Games |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n|2nd\n|'''1st''' (North East)\n|7th\n|-\n|2015<ref name = \"CFLeaderboard\"/>\n|2nd\n|'''1st''' (East)\n|'''1st'''\n|-\n|2016<ref name = \"CFLeaderboard\"/>\n|'''1st'''\n|'''1st''' (East)\n|7th\n|-\n|2017<ref name = \"CFLeaderboard\"/>\n|'''1st'''\n|'''1st''' (East)\n|'''1st'''\n|-\n|2018<ref name = \"CFLeaderboard\"/>\n|'''1st'''\n|'''1st''' (Central)\n|'''1st'''\n|-\n!Year\n!Games\n!Qualifier\n!Open\n|-\n|[[2019 CrossFit Games|2019]]\n| '''1st'''\n| '''1st''' ({{abbr|Dubai|Dubai CrossFit Championships}})<br>'''1st''' ({{abbr|Rogue|Rogue Invitational}})\n| '''1st''' (world)<br>'''1st''' (United States)\n|-\n|[[2020 CrossFit Games|2020]]\n| \n| '''1st''' ({{abbr|SiD|Strength in Depth}})<ref>{{cite web |url=https://strengthindepth.com/crossfit-strength-in-depth/leaderboards/ |title=Strength in Depth Leaderboards |access-date=January 27, 2020 |website=Strength in Depth}}</ref>\n| 2nd (world)<br>'''1st''' (United States)\n|}\n\n==Training==\n\nFraser came from an [[Olympic weightlifting]] background before injuring his back in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jtsstrength.com/articles/2015/07/30/interview-with-crossfit-superstar-mat-fraser/ |title=Interview with Crossfit Superstar Mat Fraser |website=jsstrength.com |access-date=February 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217104319/http://www.jtsstrength.com/articles/2015/07/30/interview-with-crossfit-superstar-mat-fraser |archive-date=February 17, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Since switching to [[CrossFit]], he has not followed any sort of routine training program due to the constantly varied movements found in CrossFit and the [[CrossFit Games]]. In 2017, he moved to [[Cookeville, Tennessee]].\n\nBefore the 2015 CrossFit Games, he did not maintain a strict diet and would often eat an entire pint of ice cream or a half dozen donuts. After coming in second to [[Ben Smith (CrossFit)|Ben Smith]] in 2015, he changed to a more strict diet and dropped ten pounds, although he still does not adhere to a specific diet such as [[Paleolithic diet|paleo]] or [[Nutrient#Macronutrient|counting macros]], which is common in CrossFit. Fraser tends to eat four to five big meals a day which include mainly meat and vegetables, along with sticky white rice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mensjournal.com/health-fitness/want-to-be-a-crossfit-games-champ-heres-your-training-guide-w433559/ |title=Want to Be a CrossFit Games Champion? Here\u2019s Your Guide |work=[[Men's Journal]] |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn preparation for the 2019 CrossFit Games, he trained regularly with reigning female champion [[Tia-Clair Toomey]] and her coach/husband Shane Orr.<ref>https://www.scmp.com/sport/outdoor/crossfit-strongman/article/3002784/crossfit-open-195-mat-fraser-and-tia-clair-toomey</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Footer CrossFit Games Champions Men}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fraser, Mathew}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American sportsmen]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Vermont]]\n[[Category:CrossFit athletes]]\n[[Category:University of Vermont alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professional CrossFit athlete|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{other people|Matthew Fraser}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Mathew Fraser\n| image = Mathew Fraser 1.jpg\n| caption = \n| sport = [[CrossFit]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1990|01|25}}\n| birth_place = \n| spouse = \n| education = [[University of Vermont]], [[Northern Michigan University]]\n| residence = [[Cookeville, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| height = 5 ft 7 in<ref name=\"crossfit.com\">{{cite web |title=Mathew Fraser |url=https://games.crossfit.com/athlete/153604 |website=games.crossfit.com |publisher=[[Crossfit]] |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n| weight = 195 lb<ref name=\"crossfit.com\"/>\n| occupation = [[CrossFit Games|CrossFit Athlete]]\n| pb = \n| worlds = {{unbulleted list| 2014 CrossFit Games Runner-Up | 2015 CrossFit Games Runner-Up | 2016 CrossFit Ga