ouniontribune.com/news/2015/jul/24/fittest-in-fierce-fight-at-crossFit-games/|website = San Diego Union Tribune|accessdate = 11 October 2015}}</ref> to win in 2015, but was edged out in the final event by [[Ben Smith (CrossFit)|Ben Smith]].  The following year, Fraser took first place by a commanding margin, and Smith took second. Fraser is the second person to win four consecutive CrossFit Games titles, with Rich Froning Jr. being the first.\n\nHe is the son of Canadian Olympic figure skaters [[Don Fraser (figure skater)|Don Fraser]] and [[Candace Jones]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://games.crossfit.com/article/real-deal-mat-fraser |title=The Real Deal: Mat Fraser |publisher=CrossFit Games |date=July 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==CrossFit Games results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Year\n!Games\n!Regionals\n!Open\n|-\n|2014<ref name = \"CFLeaderboard\">{{cite web |url=http://games.crossfit.com/leaderboard |title=CrossFit Games Leaderboard |publisher=CrossFit Games |accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n|2nd\n|'''1st''' (North East)\n|7th\n|-\n|2015<ref name = \"CFLeaderboard\"/>\n|2nd\n|'''1st''' (East)\n|'''1st'''\n|-\n|2016<ref name = \"CFLeaderboard\"/>\n|'''1st'''\n|'''1st''' (East)\n|7th\n|-\n|2017<ref name = \"CFLeaderboard\"/>\n|'''1st'''\n|'''1st''' (East)\n|'''1st'''\n|-\n|2018<ref name = \"CFLeaderboard\"/>\n|'''1st'''\n|'''1st''' (Central)\n|'''1st'''\n|-\n!Year\n!Games\n!Qualifier\n!Open\n|-\n|[[2019 CrossFit Games|2019]]\n| '''1st'''\n| '''1st''' ({{abbr|Dubai|Dubai CrossFit Championships}})<br>'''1st''' ({{abbr|Rogue|Rogue Invitational}})\n| '''1st''' (world)<br>'''1st''' (United States)\n|-\n|[[2020 CrossFit Games|2020]]\n| \n| '''1st''' ({{abbr|SiD|Strength in Depth}})<ref>{{cite web |url=https://strengthindepth.com/crossfit-strength-in-depth/leaderboards/ |title=Strength in Depth Leaderboards |access-date=January 27, 2020 |website=Strength in Depth}}</ref>\n| 2nd (world)<br>'''1st''' (United States)\n|}\n\n==Training==\n\nFraser came from an [[Olympic weightlifting]] background before injuring his back in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jtsstrength.com/articles/2015/07/30/interview-with-crossfit-superstar-mat-fraser/ |title=Interview with Crossfit Superstar Mat Fraser |website=jsstrength.com |access-date=February 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217104319/http://www.jtsstrength.com/articles/2015/07/30/interview-with-crossfit-superstar-mat-fraser |archive-date=February 17, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Since switching to [[CrossFit]], he has not followed any sort of routine training program due to the constantly varied movements found in CrossFit and the [[CrossFit Games]]. In 2017, he moved to [[Cookeville, Tennessee]].\n\nBefore the 2015 CrossFit Games, he did not maintain a strict diet and would often eat an entire pint of ice cream or a half dozen donuts. After coming in second to [[Ben Smith (CrossFit)|Ben Smith]] in 2015, he changed to a more strict diet and dropped ten pounds, although he still does not adhere to a specific diet such as [[Paleolithic diet|paleo]] or [[Nutrient#Macronutrient|counting macros]], which is common in CrossFit. Fraser tends to eat four to five big meals a day which include mainly meat and vegetables, along with sticky white rice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mensjournal.com/health-fitness/want-to-be-a-crossfit-games-champ-heres-your-training-guide-w433559/ |title=Want to Be a CrossFit Games Champion? Here\u2019s Your Guide |work=[[Men's Journal]] |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn preparation for the 2019 CrossFit Games, he trained regularly with reigning female champion [[Tia-Clair Toomey]] and her coach/husband Shane Orr.<ref>https://www.scmp.com/sport/outdoor/crossfit-strongman/article/3002784/crossfit-open-195-mat-fraser-and-tia-clair-toomey</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Footer CrossFit Games Champions Men}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fraser, Mathew}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American sportsmen]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Vermont]]\n[[Category:CrossFit athletes]]\n[[Category:University of Vermont alumni]]\n", "name_user": "CatCafe", "label": "safe", "comment": "head tags", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mat_Fraser_(athlete)"}
{"title_page": "Fort Valley (Virginia)", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox valley\n| name = Fort Valley\n| photo = Fort_Valley_air.jpg\n| photo_caption = Air photo of Fort Valley, facing south, with the North (right) and South (left) Forks of the [[Shenandoah River]] visible.  February 2009.\n| location = [[Shenandoah County, Virginia|Shenandoah County]], [[Virginia]]\n| elevation = \n| direction = North to south\n| length = {{Convert|23|mi|km}}\n| width = \n| boundaries = [[Massanutten Mountain]] (all sides)\n| coordinates = {{Coord|38.800|-78.461|display=inline,title|region:US-VA_type:landmark_dim:20000}}\n| topo = \n| towns = \n| traversed = S.R. 678\n}}\n'''Fort Valley''' is a [[mountain]] [[valley]] in [[Shenandoah County, Virginia|Shenandoah County]], [[Virginia]].<ref name=GNIS>{{cite GNIS|1483500|Fort Valley|December 12, 2016}}</ref>  It is often called \"valley within a valley\" as it lies between the two arms of the northern part of the [[Massanutten Mountain]] range in the [[Shenandoah Valley]], part of the  in the [[Ridge-and-Valley Appalachians]] geological zone.  \n\nThe eastern ridgeline of Fort Valley is named Massanutten Mountain and is basically continuous for the eastern length of Fort Valley, with a short stretch called Waterfall Mountain in the extreme south of the valley.  The western ridgeline of the valley, also part of the greater Massanutten range, is composed primarily of three named mountains, from north to south: Three Top Mountain, Powell Mountain and Short Mountain. Additionally, behind Three Top and Powell mountains another ridgeline in the chain is called Green Mountain with a smaller highland valley in between, called Little Fort Valley. The far southern end of Fort Valley also contains a small highland sub-valley called Crisman's Hollow, between Catback and Kerns mountains. In addition, there are several other named smaller mountains, knobs, notches and mountain gaps within the ridges of Fort Valley.\n\nFort Valley is almost entirely enclosed. At its southern end it is enclosed with an access point named Moreland Gap, and to the north it is constricted and nearly closed but for where [[Passage Creek]] flows through a narrow gap providing passage towards Front Royal. Passage Creek also is a prominent element of Fort Valley, running the entire length of the valley at its center, starting in Crishman Hollow in the mountain in the southernmost valley and flowing north, fed by other streams and runs, until it exits Fort Valley just past Elizabeth Furnace. The valley opens out toward the center, becoming about {{convert|3|mi|spell=in}} wide at its widest. The extreme southern end of the valley, the highlands of Crishman Hollow, is in Page County. The remainder of Fort Valley is in Shenandoah County, with the border of Shenandoah and Page counties being along the eastern ridgeline of Masanutten Mountain.  In all, Fort Valley is {{convert|23|mi}} long. \n\nFort Valley is entirely rural, consisting mostly of private farmland, surrounded by the [[George Washington National Forest]] (GWNF), which covers the slopes and ridges on both the east and west mountains. The [[Elizabeth Furnace]] and [[Camp Roosevelt Recreation Area]] of the GWNF are located within Fort Valley. \n\n==Roads and Gaps==\n\nBetween Three Top, Powell and Green Mountain there are two significant gaps, Mine Gap and Woodstock Gap, the latter of which features a dirt road, Rt 758, from the town of  Woodstock to the [https://www.fs.usda.gov/wps/portal/fsinternet/cs/recarea?ss=110808&navtype=BROWSEBYSUBJECT&cid=FSE_003738&navid=110240000000000&pnavid=110000000000000&position=generalinfo&recid=74047&ttype=recarea&pname=Woodstock%20Tower%20Observation%20Site Woodstock Tower], which sits on the ridge of Powell Mountain.  Woodstock Tower offers panoramic views of the town and the Shenandoah Valley and was built by the Civilian Conservation Corps in 1935. \n\nBetween Powell and Short mountains is Edinburg Gap, a more frequently traveled paved road that offers primary access from the west into Fort Valley. At the top of Edinburg Gap on the southern side there is an extensive all terrain vehicle (ATV) trail system set up by the Forest Service. On the northern side of the gap starts Peter's Mill Road, an off-highway vehicle (OHV) road made available for jeeps and four wheel drive vehicles. Peter's Mill Road runs from Edinburg Gap to Woodstock Gap along the higher reaches of the Little Fort Valley. In the east, Fort Valley is accessed via a paved road through Edith Gap that also serves as entrance to Camp Roosevelt Recreation Area. There are no roads accessing Fort Valley over Massanutten Mountain from Camp Roosevelt on the southeast to Elizabeth furnace at the northern apex of the valley.\n\nRoads exit the valley at its northern end ([[Virginia State Route 678|S.R. 678]]) between [[Strasburg, Virginia|Strasburg]] and [[Front Royal, Virginia|Front Royal]], at Edinburg Gap ([[Virginia State Route 675|S.R. 675]]) towards [[Edinburg, Virginia|Edinburg]], Moreland Gap ([[Virginia State Route 730|S.R. 730]]) towards [[New Market, Virginia|New Market]], and Edith Gap (S.R. 675) towards [[Luray, Virginia|Luray]]. There is also the dirt road that leads to [[Woodstock, Virginia|Woodstock]] ([[Virginia State Route 758|S.R 758]]) over Powell Mountain.\n\n==Hiking Trails and Recreation Areas==\n\nThe [[Tuscarora_Trail|Tuscarora trail]], a 252-mile long distance hiking trail that passes through Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland,  Pennsylvania, proceeds along the northeast ridgeline of Fort Valley, entering from just above [https://www.dcr.virginia.gov/state-parks/shenandoah-river Shenandoah State Park] on the eastern ridgeline of Massanutten Mountain. The hiking trail passes through the Elizabeth Furnace Recreation Area, ascends Green Mountain and exits on Doll's Ridge on the western slope of Three Top Mountain as it descends towards the [[Tom's Brook Battlefield]] in the Shenandoah Valley. \n\nThe [[Massanutten Trail]] circumnavigates the entire ridgeline of the Fort Valley, 71 miles in total. It was built by the Potomac Appalachian Trail Club (PATC), completed in 2001. Prior to 2001, different portions of the trail had been known by different names and blazed in different colors. With the completion of the missing links, the Forest Service renamed the combined trails as the Massanutten Trail and provided orange blazes along the trail's entire length around Fort Valley.\n\nFort Valley features two developed U.S. Forest Service recreation areas, [https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/gwj/recarea/?recid=73687 Elizabeth Furnace Recreation Area] toward the northern apex of the Valley, and [https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/gwj/recarea/?recid=73633 Camp Roosevelt Recreation Area] at Edith Gap in the southeast end of the valley. Both recreation areas were built by the Civilian Conservation Corps in the 1930s. Camp Roosevelt features a hang gliding site nearby, a pavilion, camp sites and access to the Masanutten Trail.  Elizabeth Furnace Recreation Area features a pavilion and multiple camping areas, interpretive trails related the historical iron industry at the site, and acess to the Masanutten and Tuscarora trails which share a length of trail leading to Elizabeth Furnace from the east and separate at Elizabeth Furnace north (Massanutten Trail) and west (Tuscarora Trail.)\n\n==Special Biological Areas==\n\nThe ridges of Fort Valley administered by the U.S. Forest Service contain several Special Biological Areas (SBA). These include Mudhole Gap SBA in the northern end of the Little Fort Valley; Peters Mill Run Bog SBA in the upper reaches of the Little Fort Valley area just south of Woodstock Tower; Signal Knob SBA and the Edinburg Gap Shale Barrens SBA, two of the easternmost Appalachian shale barrens <ref>https://www.conservationgateway.org/ConservationByGeography/NorthAmerica/UnitedStates/edc/Documents/HabitatGuides/13.pdf</ref>; and Scothorn Gap SBA, a 34 acre forest plan-designated Special Biological Area in the southernmost edge of Masanutten Mountain. Waterfall Mountain Cliffs, in the southern extremity of the Fort Valley's Masanutten Mountain ridgeline just south of Scothorn Gap, has been recommended by Virginia Division of Natural Heritage to be designated as a Special Biological Area as it contains significant amounts of semi-primitive acreage.<ref>http://www.vawilderness.org/uploads/1/7/4/4/17446555/massanutten.pdf</ref>\n\n==History==\nFort Valley was a native American hunting ground. The name Massanutten is said to mean \"Indian Basket,\" the Fort Valley being contained and perhaps shaped like an Indian basket and certainly abounding in wild game in early times.<ref>http://www.vagenweb.org/shenandoah/hom/S_pfv.html</ref>  While no permanent settlements were located there, Indian relics have been found on several temporary village sites. In 1740s Massanutten Mountain was called Peaked Mountain, and later it was known as Buffalo Mountain. George Washington surveyed Fort Valley for [[Lord Fairfax]] in 1748<ref>http://www.patc.us/history/archive/massntn.html</ref>.\n\nA first settler named Powell, reputed to be a fugitive from the law, took refuge in the valley in the northwestern mountain. Likely because it was not easily accessible in the colonial era, the area was then called Powell's Fort Mountain or Powell's Fort Valley, and later just \"The Fort.\" The area Powell inhabited is now known as Powell's Mountain, and Fort Valley. Powell is said to have found silver or gold in the area. About 1733, three frontier hunters settled in \"The Fort\" and others soon followed.<ref>http://www.patc.us/history/archive/massntn.html</ref>\n\nAccording to tradition, [[Daniel Morgan]] built the first road into Fort Valley at the order of [[George Washington]], with a view to holing up in this naturally fortified valley as a possible winter retreat had the Continental Army been defeated by the [[British Army|British]] during the [[American Revolution]]. Washington had spent extensive time surveying the valley in his earlier life, and likely had  been impressed by the natural defenses offered by the mountain-contained valley. Thirty years later, after a hard winter at Valley Forge, Washington stated that if the war did not turn in their favor by the next winter, rather than surrender the Army would move south to the Shenandoah and make a stand in \"The Fort.\" About this time Morgan reportedly began building a road into the valley, but when the Continental armies had success work stopped.<ref>http://www.patc.us/history/archive/massntn.html</ref> Primary access would have been through a high pass now called Sherman's Gap along rough road partially constructed by Morgan; the route became known as Morgan's Road. Portions of the road are still visible and accessible by a hiking trail near Sherman's Gap, but in lower elevations the route is lost and unknown. In any case, the [[Continental Army]]'s victory at [[Siege of Yorktown|Yorktown]] made Washington's theoretical plans unnecessary. Why Morgan would have picked a military road over a nearly 2,000 foot minor gap as opposed an easier route along the water line of Passage Creek is unclear, leading some to believe the story is apocryphal. \n\n[[Elizabeth Furnace]] was a blast furnace in the Shenandoah Valley that created pig iron from 1836 \u2013 1888, using Passage Creek for water power. Iron ore was mined in the mountains, purified in the furnace, then pig iron was transported transported over Massanutten Mountain to the South Fork of the Shenandoah River, where it was transported for forging in Harpers Ferry, Virginia (later West Virginia.) The road used to transport the iron is in use today as a hiking trail. At one time, Elizabeth Furnace supported a community associated with the local iron industry. Elizabeth Furnace was destroyed by Union troops in 1864 during operations associated with the [[Battle of Cedar Creek]]. The furnace reopened in 1883 but lacked sufficient output to be competitive with new mines in the midwest, and was abandoned in 1888. The Elizabeth Furnace Cabin is one of the few wooden buildings remaining from the early 1800s when Elizabeth Furnace was active. <ref>https://shenandoahcountyva.us/tourism/wp-content/uploads/sites/16/2014/01/Elizabeth_Furnace_rec_Area_info_booklet-sm-res1.pdf</ref>. In 1936 the Civilian Conservation Corps constructed the Elizabeth Furnace Recreation Area on the site.\n\nSignal Knob, a 2,111 foot barren promontory at the extreme northern ridgeline of Fort Valley offering sweeping panoramic views of of the Shenandoah Valley northeast and west, was utilized during a Civil War as an important Confederate military observation post. In skirmishing over control of Signal Knob, several Confederate soldiers were killed. One still lies buried there and his grave that inspired the poem, \"The Georgia Volunteer.\"<ref>http://www.patc.us/history/archive/massntn.html</ref> From Signal Knob the view of the Shenandoah Valley battlefields of Cedar Creek, [[Fisher's Hill]] and Tom's Brook is unobstructed. Signal Knob is accessed by an 11.5 mile round-trip hike from Elizabeth Furnace. Otherwise, during the Civil War no battle was fought in Fort Valley, but [[General Imboden]]'s cavalry camped there at times.<ref>http://www.patc.us/history/archive/massntn.html</ref>\n\nThe [[Daniel Munch House]] was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2002.<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Landforms of Shenandoah County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Virginia]]\n\n\n{{ShenandoahCountyVA-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox valley\n| name = Fort Valley\n| photo = Fort_Valley_air.jpg\n| photo_caption = Air photo of Fort Valley, facing south, with the North (right) and South (left) Forks of the [[Shenandoah River]] visible.  February 2009.\n| location = [[Shenandoah County, Virginia|Shenandoah County]], [[Virginia]]\n| elevation = \n| direction = North to south\n| length = {{Convert|23|mi|km}}\n| width = \n| boundaries = [[Massanutten Mountain]] (all sides)\n| coordinates = {{Coord|38.800|-78.461|display=inline,title|region:US-VA_type:landmark_dim:20000}}\n| topo = \n| towns = \n| traversed = S.R. 678\n}}\n'''Fort Valley''' is a [[mountain]] [[valley]] in [[Shenandoah County, Virginia|Shenandoah County]], [[Virginia]].<ref name=GNIS>{{cite GNIS|1483500|Fort Valley|December 12, 2016}}</ref>  It is often called \"valley within a valley\" as it lies between the two arms of the northern part of the [[Massanutten Mountain]] range in the [[Shenandoah Valley]], part of the  in the [[Ridge-and-Valley Appalachians]] geological zone.  \n\nThe eastern ridgeline of Fort Valley is named Massanutten Mountain and is basically continuous for the eastern length of Fort Valley, with a short stretch called Waterfall Mountain in the extreme south of the valley.  The western ridgeline of the valley, also part of the greater Massanutten range, is composed primarily of three named mountains, from north to south: Three Top Mountain, Powell Mountain and Short Mountain. Additionally, behind Three Top and Powell mountains another ridgeline in the chain is called Green Mountain with a smaller highland valley in between, called Little Fort Valley. The far southern end of Fort Valley also contains a small highland sub-valley called Crisman's Hollow, between Catback and Kerns mountains. In addition, there are several other named smaller mountains, knobs, notches and mountain gaps within the ridges of Fort Valley.\n\nFort Valley is almost entirely enclosed. At its southern end it is enclosed with an access point named Moreland Gap, and to the north it is constricted and nearly closed but for where [[Passage Creek]] flows through a narrow gap providing passage towards Front Royal. Passage Creek also is a prominent element of Fort Valley, running the entire length of the valley at its center, starting in Crishman Hollow in the mountain in the southernmost valley and flowing north, fed by other streams and runs, until it exits Fort Valley just past Elizabeth Furnace. The valley opens out toward the center, becoming about {{convert|3|mi|spell=in}} wide at its widest. The extreme southern end of the valley, the highlands of Crishman Hollow, is in Page County. The remainder of Fort Valley is in Shenandoah County, with the border of Shenandoah and Page counties being along the eastern ridgeline of Masanutten Mountain.  In all, Fort Valley is {{convert|23|mi}} long. \n\nFort Valley is entirely rural, consisting mostly of private farmland, surrounded by the [[George Washington National Forest]] (GWNF), which covers the slopes and ridges on both the east and west mountains. The [[Elizabeth Furnace]] and [[Camp Roosevelt Recreation Area]] of the GWNF are located within Fort Valley. \n\n==Roads and Gaps==\n\nBetween Three Top, Powell and Green Mountain there are two significant gaps, Mine Gap and Woodstock Gap, the latter of which features a dirt road, Rt 758, from the town of  Woodstock to the [https://www.fs.usda.gov/wps/portal/fsinternet/cs/recarea?ss=110808&navtype=BROWSEBYSUBJECT&cid=FSE_003738&navid=110240000000000&pnavid=110000000000000&position=generalinfo&recid=74047&ttype=recarea&pname=Woodstock%20Tower%20Observation%20Site Woodstock Tower], which sits on the ridge of Powell Mountain.  Woodstock Tower offers panoramic views of the town and the Shenandoah Valley and was built by the Civilian Conservation Corps in 1935. \n\nBetween Powell and Short mountains is Edinburg Gap, a more frequently traveled paved road that offers primary access from the west into Fort Valley. At the top of Edinburg Gap on the southern side there is an extensive all terrain vehicle (ATV) trail system set up by the Forest Service. On the northern side of the gap starts Peter's Mill Road, an off-highway vehicle (OHV) road made available for jeeps and four wheel drive vehicles. Peter's Mill Road runs from Edinburg Gap to Woodstock Gap along the higher reaches of the Little Fort Valley. In the east, Fort Valley is accessed via a paved road through Edith Gap that also serves as entrance to Camp Roosevelt Recreation Area. There are no roads accessing Fort Valley over Massanutten Mountain from Camp Roosevelt on the southeast to Elizabeth furnace at the northern apex of the valley.\n\nRoads exit the valley at its northern end ([[Virginia State Route 678|S.R. 678]]) between [[Strasburg, Virginia|Strasburg]] and [[Front Royal, Virginia|Front Royal]], at Edinburg Gap ([[Virginia State Route 675|S.R. 675]]) towards [[Edinburg, Virginia|Edinburg]], Moreland Gap ([[Virginia State Route 730|S.R. 730]]) towards [[New Market, Virginia|New Market]], and Edith Gap (S.R. 675) towards [[Luray, Virginia|Luray]]. There is also the dirt road that leads to [[Woodstock, Virginia|Woodstock]] ([[Virginia State Route 758|S.R 758]]) over Powell Mountain.\n\n==Hiking Trails and Recreation Areas==\n\nThe [[Tuscarora_Trail|Tuscarora trail]], a 252-mile long distance hiking trail that passes through Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland,  Pennsylvania, proceeds along the northeast ridgeline of Fort Valley, entering from just above [https://www.dcr.virginia.gov/state-parks/shenandoah-river Shenandoah State Park] on the eastern ridgeline of Massanutten Mountain. The hiking trail passes through the Elizabeth Furnace Recreation Area, ascends Green Mountain and exits on Doll's Ridge on the western slope of Three Top Mountain as it descends towards the [[Tom's Brook Battlefield]] in the Shenandoah Valley. \n\nThe [[Massanutten Trail]] circumnavigates the entire ridgeline of the Fort Valley, 71 miles in total. It was built by the Potomac Appalachian Trail Club (PATC), completed in 2001. Prior to 2001, different portions of the trail had been known by different names and blazed in different colors. With the completion of the missing links, the Forest Service renamed the combined trails as the Massanutten Trail and provided orange blazes along the trail's entire length around Fort Valley.\n\nFort Valley features two developed U.S. Forest Service recreation areas, [https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/gwj/recarea/?recid=73687 Elizabeth Furnace Recreation Area] toward the northern apex of the Valley, and [https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/gwj/recarea/?recid=73633 Camp Roosevelt Recreation Area] at Edith Gap in the southeast end of the valley. Both recreation areas were built by the Civilian Conservation Corps in the 1930s. Camp Roosevelt features a hang gliding site nearby, a pavilion, camp sites and access to the Masanutten Trail.  Elizabeth Furnace Recreation Area features a pavilion and multiple camping areas, interpretive trails related the historical iron industry at the site, and acess to the Masanutten and Tuscarora trails which share a length of trail leading to Elizabeth Furnace from the east and separate at Elizabeth Furnace north (Massanutten Trail) and west (Tuscarora Trail.)\n\n==Special Biological Areas==\n\nThe ridges of Fort Valley administered by the U.S. Forest Service contain several Special Biological Areas (SBA). These include Mudhole Gap SBA in the northern end of the Little Fort Valley; Peters Mill Run Bog SBA in the upper reaches of the Little Fort Valley area just south of Woodstock Tower; Signal Knob SBA and the Edinburg Gap Shale Barrens SBA, two of the easternmost Appalachian shale barrens <ref>https://www.conservationgateway.org/ConservationByGeography/NorthAmerica/UnitedStates/edc/Documents/HabitatGuides/13.pdf</ref>; and Scothorn Gap SBA, a 34 acre forest plan-designated Special Biological Area in the southernmost edge of Masanutten Mountain. Waterfall Mountain Cliffs, in the southern extremity of the Fort Valley's Masanutten Mountain ridgeline just south of Scothorn Gap, has been recommended by Virginia Division of Natural Heritage to be designated as a Special Biological Area as it contains significant amounts of semi-primitive acreage.<ref>http://www.vawilderness.org/uploads/1/7/4/4/17446555/massanutten.pdf</ref>\n\n==History==\nFort Valley was a native American hunting ground. The name Massanutten is said to mean \"Indian Basket,\" the Fort Valley being contained and perhaps shaped like an Indian basket and certainly abounding in wild game in early times.<ref>http://www.vagenweb.org/shenandoah/hom/S_pfv.html</ref>  While no permanent settlements were located there, Indian relics have been found on several temporary village sites. In 1740s Massanutten Mountain was called Peaked Mountain, and later it was known as Buffalo Mountain. George Washington surveyed Fort Valley for [[Lord Fairfax]] in 1748<ref>http://www.patc.us/history/archive/massntn.html</ref>.\n\nA first settler named Powell, reputed to be a fugitive from the law, took refuge in the valley in the northwestern mountain. Likely because it was not easily accessible in the colonial era, the area was then called Powell's Fort Mountain or Powell's Fort Valley, and later just \"The Fort.\" The area Powell inhabited is now known as Powell's Mountain, and Fort Valley. Powell is said to have found silver or gold in the area. About 1733, three frontier hunters settled in \"The Fort\" and others soon followed.<ref>http://www.patc.us/history/archive/massntn.html</ref>\n\nAccording to tradition, [[Daniel Morgan]] built the first road into Fort Valley at the order of [[George Washington]], with a view to holing up in this naturally fortified valley as a possible winter retreat had the Continental Army been defeated by the [[British Army|British]] during the [[American Revolution]]. Washington had spent extensive time surveying the valley in his earlier life, and likely had  been impressed by the natural defenses offered by the mountain-contained valley. Thirty years later, after a hard winter at Valley Forge, Washington stated that if the war did not turn in their favor by the next winter, rather than surrender the Army would move south to the Shenandoah and make a stand in \"The Fort.\" About this time Morgan reportedly began building a road into the valley, but when the Continental armies had success work stopped.<ref>http://www.patc.us/history/archive/massntn.html</ref> Primary access would have been through a high pass now called Sherman's Gap along rough road partially constructed by Morgan; the route became known as Morgan's Road. Portions of the road are still visible and accessible by a hiking trail near Sherman's Gap, but in lower elevations the route is lost and unknown. In any case, the [[Continental Army]]'s victory at [[Siege of Yorktown|Yorktown]] made Washington's theoretical plans unnecessary. Why Morgan would have picked a military road over a nearly 2,000 foot minor gap as opposed an easier route along the water line of Passage Creek is unclear, leading some to believe the story is apocryphal. \n\n[[Elizabeth Furnace]] was a blast furnace in the Shenandoah Valley that created pig iron from 1836 \u2013 1888, using Passage Creek for water power. Iron ore was mined in the mountains, purified in the furnace, then pig iron was transported transported over Massanutten Mountain to the South Fork of the Shenandoah River, where it was transported for forging in Harpers Ferry, Virginia (later West Virginia.) The road used to transport the iron is in use today as a hiking trail. At one time, Elizabeth Furnace supported a community associated with the local iron industry. Elizabeth Furnace was destroyed by Union troops in 1864 during operations associated with the [[Battle of Cedar Creek]]. The furnace reopened in 1883 but lacked sufficient output to be competitive with new mines in the midwest, and was abandoned in 1888. The Elizabeth Furnace Cabin is one of the few wooden buildings remaining from the early 1800s when Elizabeth Furnace was active. <ref>https://shenandoahcountyva.us/tourism/wp-content/uploads/sites/16/2014/01/Elizabeth_Furnace_rec_Area_info_booklet-sm-res1.pdf</ref>. In 1936 the Civilian Conservation Corps constructed the Elizabeth Furnace Recreation Area on the site.\n\nSignal Knob, a 2,111 foot barren promontory at the extreme northern ridgeline of Fort Valley offering sweeping panoramic views of of the Shenandoah Valley northeast and west, was utilized during a Civil War as an important Confederate military observation post. In skirmishing over control of Signal Knob, several Confederate soldiers were killed. One still lies buried there and his grave that inspired the poem, \"The Georgia Volunteer.\"<ref>http://www.patc.us/history/archive/massntn.html</ref> From Signal Knob the view of the Shenandoah Valley battlefields of Cedar Creek, [[Fisher's Hill]] and Tom's Brook is unobstructed. Signal Knob is accessed by an 11.5 mile round-trip hike from Elizabeth Furnace. Otherwise during the Civil War no battle was fought in Fort Valley, but [[General Imboden]]'s cavalry camped there at times.<ref>http://www.patc.us/history/archive/massntn.html</ref>\n\nThe [[Daniel Munch House]] was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2002.<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Landforms of Shenandoah County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Virginia]]\n\n\n{{ShenandoahCountyVA-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Woodrusher", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fort_Valley_(Virginia)"}
{"title_page": "Wendy Francis", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=April 2013}}{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Wendy Francis\n| honorific_suffix =\n| image       = File:Wendy Francis Australian Christian Lobby.png\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  = Wendy Francis\n| birth_date  = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Birth-date and age|Month DD, YYYY}} -->\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place =\n| nationality =\n| other_names =\n| occupation  = [[Lobbyist]]\n| known_for   =\n}}\n'''Wendy Francis''' is an Australian homophobic political activist. She is a lobbyist against LGBTQI+ issues and is the [[Queensland]] state director of the [[Australian Christian Lobby]] (ACL).\n\n== Biography ==\nWendy Francis was the Executive Producer of the [[Carols in the City|Brisbane Lord Mayor's Christmas Carols]] for several years. She is married to Peter Francis, who is a Baptist pastor and Vice-Principal, lecturer and Director of Field Education at [[Malyon College]].<ref name=\"Background\">{{cite news |url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/who-is-wendy-francis-20110603-1fkbe.html|title=Who is Wendy Francis? |author=Moore, Tony |date=3 June 2011|work=[[The Brisbane Times]] |publisher= |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nFrancis' political interests before joining ACL in January 2011 included her running as the lead Senate candidate in Queensland for the [[Family First Party]] in the 2010 Federal election.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.acl.org.au/our-staff/|title=Our Staff  |author= | date = |work=[[Australian Christian Lobby|ACL]] |accessdate=6 April 2013}}</ref> She created controversy when she compared allowing same-sex marriage to the [[stolen generations]] and to \"legalising child abuse\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/technology/technology-news/family-first-candidate-wendy-francis-stands-by-gay--slur-on-twitter-20100809-11s5c.html|title=Family First candidate Wendy Francis stands by gay slur on Twitter |author=Grubb, Ben |date=9 August 2010|work=[[The Age]] |publisher= |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nChad St James, the Brisbane editor of ''SameSame'',  said of Wendy Francis:\n<blockquote>\"Over a couple of hours sitting in a cafe, the two of us chatted and for the very first time I saw very human side to a woman who has been one of our most stringent opponents to marriage equality. I also gained a better understanding of her motivations, and I won\u2019t deny that it was one of the most surprising coffee dates I have had a long time\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205024920/http://www.samesame.com.au/features/8830/Coffee-with-Wendy-Francis.htm |author=St James, Chad |date=27 August 2012|title=Coffee with Wendy Francis |work=SameSame|publisher= |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nFrancis shared a personal story on Brisbane radio on the impact of her sister's death.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.abc.net.au/queensland/2013/03/the-view-from-brisbane-wendy-francis.html?site=brisbane&program=612_breakfast|title=The View From Brisbane - Wendy Francis |author=Levingston, Rebecca |date=25 March 2013 |work=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] |publisher= |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Lobbying==\nSince 2007, Francis has run 'meet the candidate forums' for ACL in 15 to 20 Queensland electorates in each election.<ref name = \"elections\">{{cite news|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/opinion/opinion-dont-be-fooled-labor-supports-safe-schools/news-story/c787a1a091be8d7dff58c1ff16075a0c  |title=Opinion: Don\u2019t be fooled, Labor supports Safe Schools |author=Dean, Rownan|date=13 November 2017|work=Courier Mail|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August 2010 Francis tweeted \"Children in homosexual relationships are subject to emotional abuse. Legitimising gay marriage is like legalising child abuse.\"  Francis later deleted the tweet but stood by her comments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/family-first-candidate-wendy-francis-stands-by-gay--slur-on-twitter-20100809-11s5c.html|title=Family First candidate Wendy Francis stands by gay slur on Twitter|last=Grubb|first=Ben|date=2010-08-09|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n\nDuring April 2013, Francis lobbied against government subsidies for the abortion drug [[Mifepristone|RU486]] saying, \"Women facing unsupported pregnancies should be offered real support - not a chemical which is harmful to both them and their unborn child.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-national/ru486-drug-wont-lead-to-more-abortions-20130426-2iizk.html | title=RU486 drug 'won't lead to more abortions' |author=Bennet, Adam |date=26 April 2013|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |publisher= |accessdate=5 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nFrancis has argued for [[Billboard|outdoor advertising]] to be \u2018[[Australian Classification Board|G-rated]]\u2019.<ref name=\"Background\"/> She organised ACL members to protest against bus shelter billboards - where as Francis said, \"children are waiting for the school bus\" - promoting [[safe sex]], which featured a fully clothed, hugging, gay couple holding an unopened condom packet.   Francis was criticised due to her campaign not mentioning any affiliation with the ACL, and for describing the image as an act of foreplay.<ref name=\"herald\">{{cite web |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/more-news/hiv-ads-pulled-from-brisbane-bus-shelters/story-fn7x8me2-1226067288044 |title=Adshel reinstates safe sex ad after removal sparked online backlash |author= |date=1 June 2011 |work=[[Herald Sun]] |publisher= |accessdate=1 June 2011}}</ref> A Queensland Parliament committee conducted a public hearing where Francis argued that all billboards should be \u2018G-rated\u2019.  The  committee subsequently recommended a tougher approach to sexually explicit outdoor advertising.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/new-laws-may-crack-down-on-sexually-explicit-billboards/story-fnihsrf2-1226815309185|title=New laws may crack down on sexually explicit billboards|first=Robyn|last=Ironside|date=1 February 2014|publisher=[[The Courier Mail]]|accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013 after a billboard was erected in [[Kings Cross, New South Wales]], Francis lobbied to have it removed.  The billboard displayed a fictionalised UK prime minister having sex with a pig. Francis said children should not have to see an adult image like this.  The billboard was subsequently taken down.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-05-02/christian-lobby-wants-foxtel-fined-over-bestiality-billboard/4664168|title='Christian lobby urges fines for bestiality billboard |author= |date=2 May 2013 |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC]]|publisher= |accessdate=3 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013 a ruling was made against the owners of a billboard by the [[Advertising Standards Bureau (Australia)|Advertising Standards Bureau]] (ASB).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mumbrella.com.au/ad-watchdog-bans-strip-club-poster-may-show-nipple-176191  |title=Ad watchdog bans strip club poster because it may show nipple |date=3 September 2013|work=Mumbrella|accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref> The ASB said it presented women, \"in a manner that was subservient and degrading\".  The owners said they would comply with the ruling.   With the billboard remaining in place in August 2015, Francis said that self-regulation is not working.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.townsvillebulletin.com.au/news/townsville/watchdog-powerless-to-remove-raunchy-billboard/story-fnjfzsax-1227481044699  |title=Watchdog powerless to remove raunchy billboard |author=Healy, Samantha|date=13 August 2015|work=Townsville Bulletin|accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrancis has campaigned against the offensive slogans painted on the sides of [[Wicked Campers|Wicked Camper]] vans.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/07/15/christian-lobby-sees-red-over-wicked-vans  |title=Christian lobby sees red over Wicked vans |accessdate=29 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-11-17/wicked-campers-with-'vile'-slogans-to-be-outlawed-in-tasmania/8033548  |title=Wicked Campers with 'vile and appalling' slogans to be outlawed in Tasmania |accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref>  Francis has similarly campaigned against a series of ads for shoes which incorporate naked models.  The promoters say their ads are a \"celebration of sexual expression\" and are designed to \"target a younger audience\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/fashion/designers/volley-hits-back-at-australian-christian-lobbys-homophobic-response-to-ad-campaign/news-story/36c69007512fc2d2696ff22f53ddc948  |title=Volley hits back at Australian Christian Lobby\u2019s \u2018homophobic\u2019 response to ad campaign |author=Sullivan, Rebecca|date=18 January 2017|work=|accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nFrancis received abuse over her support of changes in surrogacy laws to exclude same sex couples and single people.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/christian-lobbyist-weathers-barrage-of-abuse-20120624-20w5e.html|title=Christian lobbyist weathers barrage of abuse |author=Bridie, Jabour |date=24 June 2012|work=[[The Brisbane Times]] |publisher= |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Francis lodged a petition with the [[Parliament of Queensland|Queensland parliament]] complaining about the [[Safe Schools Coalition Australia|Safe Schools program]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/australian-christian-lobby-slams-safe-schools-antibullying-program-20151103-gkq6gr.html  |title=Australian Christian Lobby slams Safe Schools anti-bullying program | author=Partridge, Emma|date=4 November 2015|work=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref> The petition incorporated wording from a Safe Schools student resource, ''OMG I\u2019m [[Queer]]'', intended for children aged 11 and up.  However the Clerk of the Parliament would not permit the wording on Queensland parliament\u2019s website because of the \"intemperate\" language.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/opinion/columnists/angela-shanahan/parents-are-the-best-judge-of-their-kids-sex-education-needs/news-story/a4735e9b23790a3769ac99d97d656253  |title=Parents are the best judge of their kids\u2019 sex education needs |author=Shanahan, Angela|date=27 February 2016|work=The Australian|accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref>  The 10,891-signature, petition was subsequently tabled with the \"intemperate\" wording censored.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/apps/Epetitions/ClosedEpetition.aspx?PetNum=2429  |title= Cease Safe Schools roll out in Queensland schools |date= 13 October 2015|accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref>  While the [[Annastacia Palaszczuk|Palaszczuk]] government has said that it does not have plans to introduce the Safe Schools program in Queensland, Francis is concerned that that could be reintroduced in some other form.<ref name = \"elections\"/><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/queensland-election/labor-plotting-to-revive-safe-schools-plan-says-christian-lobby/news-story/4b04d35a57a6a1b571b325b2f0daa4de |title=Queensland election: Labor plotting to revive Safe Schools plan, says Christian lobby |author=Urban, Rebecca|date=|work=The Australian|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref>  Francis has said that she supported anti-bullying programs, but the Safe Schools Coalition goes \"way beyond that\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.buzzfeed.com/lanesainty/this-is-why-the-australian-christian-lobby-is-talking-about |title= A Christian Group Is Up In Arms About Chest Binding And Here's Why|work =[[BuzzFeedNews]]| author=Sainty, Lane|date=13 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFrancis has campaigned against the liberalisation of abortion laws in Queensland.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/fact-and-reason-needed-in-abortion-debate-trad-20160625-gprrkn.html  |title='Fact and reason' needed in abortion debate |author=Remeikis, Amy|date=25 June 2016|work=Brisbane Times|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://catholicleader.com.au/news/pro-life-groups-urge-supporters-to-sign-petition-to-say-no-to-queensland-abortion-reforms-before-bills-are-debated-next-year  |title=Pro-life groups urge supporters to sign petition to say no to Queensland abortion reforms before Bills are debated next year |author=Bowning, Mark|date=8 December 2016|work=Catholic Leader|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> In lobbying against 'gender selection', Francis has said that eliminating human life in its early stages for being the wrong sex, is sex discrimination.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/gender-selection-family-balancing-or-vanity-parenting/news-story/88a2b43382d09c1df6e92b445c4c8a05  |title=Gender selection: Family balancing or vanity parenting? |author=Ambrose, Margaret|date=25 November 2016|work=Herald Sun|accessdate=3 December 2016}}</ref>  Francis has said that for Australian to use its foreign aid program to finance abortion in developing countries. which are culturally opposed to abortion, is a form of \"colonialism\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/australian-christian-lobby-urges-turnbull-government-to-copy-donald-trumps-foreign-aid-abortion-ban-20170314-guxpra.html  |title=Australian Christian Lobby urges Turnbull government to copy Donald Trump's foreign aid abortion ban }}</ref>\n\nFrancis also supports the 'Nordic' model of prostitution legalisation - which has been described as the world\u2019s first human rights/women\u2019s rights-based legal model of prostitution legislation. The Nordic Approach does not criminalise the prostitute, but rather it criminalises the buyer \u2014 addressing the demand for prostitution, and importantly also provides women with exit strategies. Within four years of the law being implemented, the number of women involved in prostitution in Sweden halved.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/opinion/wendy-francis-south-australia-can-lead-australia-by-introducing-worlds-most-uptodate-prostitution-legislation/news-story/b20bf6eb4d752f5faa89593289ec7045|title=SA has chance to reform sex industry|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref>\n\nIn response to children being taught that they can choose their gender, Francis has had two books published entitled, \"What are little boys made of?\" and \"What are little girls made of?\" describing how a child\u2019s biological sex determines whether they are a boy or a girl, with each sex having specific [[XY sex-determination system|X or Y chromosomes]].  Francis does not ignore the reality of children born with [[intersex]] conditions which, whilst rare, account for a number of genetic or developmental situations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.qbmagazine.org.au/what-are-little-boys-and-girls-made-of/  |title=What are little Boys and Girls Made of? |work =QB Magazine| date=24 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Centre for Human Dignity===\nFrancis heads the 'Centre for Human Dignity', which was established in 2017 by ACL<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acl.org.au/centre_for_human_dignity_united_against_sexual_exploitation  |title= Centre For Human Dignity - United Against Sexual Exploitation|author=|date=|work=Australian Christian Lobby|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref> to advocate for rights and freedoms, particularly for vulnerable children and to stand against all forms of sexual exploitation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centreforhumandignity.org.au/  |title=Centre for Human Dignity  |work=Centre for Human Dignity|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n===Books===\n* ''What are little girls made of?  What are little boys made of?'', [[Connor Court Publishing]], 2019, {{ISBN|9781925826357}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.connorcourtpublishing.com.au/What-are-little-girls-made-of-What-are-little-boys-made-of-As-a-set_p_254.html  |title=What are little girls made of?  What are little boys made of? |work =[[Connor Court Publishing]]| author=Francis, Wendy|date=May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Opinion article===\n* ''Freedom \u2013 Australia\u2019s Most Endangered Liberty'', [[Vision Christian Radio]], 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vision.org.au/radio/2017/10/19/freedom-australias-most-endangered-liberty-wendy-francis/  |title=FREEDOM \u2013 Australia\u2019s Most Endangered Liberty \u2013 Wendy Francis |work =[[Vision Christian Radio]]| author=Francis, Wendy|date=19 October 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Australia}}\n* [[Abortion in Australia]]\n* [[Australian Catholic Bishops' Conference]]\n* [[Australian Marriage Law Postal Survey]]\n* [[Christianity in Australia]]\n* [[Coalition for Marriage (Australia)]]\n* [[Euthanasia in Australia]]\n* [[FamilyVoice Australia]]\n* [[Human rights in Australia]]\n* [[Marriage Alliance]]\n* [[Marriage in Australia]]\n* [[National Organization for Marriage]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Francis, Wendy}}\n[[Category:Australian Christians]]\n[[Category:Australian lobbyists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=April 2013}}{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Wendy Francis\n| honorific_suffix =\n| image       = File:Wendy Francis Australian Christian Lobby.png\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  = Wendy Francis\n| birth_date  = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Birth-date and age|Month DD, YYYY}} -->\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place =\n| nationality =\n| other_names =\n| occupation  = [[Lobbyist]]\n| known_for   =\n}}\n'''Wendy Francis''' is an Australian political activist. She is a lobbyist on social issues and is the [[Queensland]] state director of the [[Australian Christian Lobby]] (ACL).\n\n== Biography ==\nWendy Francis was the Executive Producer of the [[Carols in the City|Brisbane Lord Mayor's Christmas Carols]] for several years. She is married to Peter Francis, who is a Baptist pastor and Vice-Principal, lecturer and Director of Field Education at [[Malyon College]].<ref name=\"Background\">{{cite news |url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/who-is-wendy-francis-20110603-1fkbe.html|title=Who is Wendy Francis? |author=Moore, Tony |date=3 June 2011|work=[[The Brisbane Times]] |publisher= |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nFrancis' political interests before joining ACL in January 2011 included her running as the lead Senate candidate in Queensland for the [[Family First Party]] in the 2010 Federal election.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.acl.org.au/our-staff/|title=Our Staff  |author= | date = |work=[[Australian Christian Lobby|ACL]] |accessdate=6 April 2013}}</ref> She created controversy when she compared allowing same-sex marriage to the [[stolen generations]] and to \"legalising child abuse\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/technology/technology-news/family-first-candidate-wendy-francis-stands-by-gay--slur-on-twitter-20100809-11s5c.html|title=Family First candidate Wendy Francis stands by gay slur on Twitter |author=Grubb, Ben |date=9 August 2010|work=[[The Age]] |publisher= |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nChad St James, the Brisbane editor of ''SameSame'',  said of Wendy Francis:\n<blockquote>\"Over a couple of hours sitting in a cafe, the two of us chatted and for the very first time I saw very human side to a woman who has been one of our most stringent opponents to marriage equality. I also gained a better understanding of her motivations, and I won\u2019t deny that it was one of the most surprising coffee dates I have had a long time\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205024920/http://www.samesame.com.au/features/8830/Coffee-with-Wendy-Francis.htm |author=St James, Chad |date=27 August 2012|title=Coffee with Wendy Francis |work=SameSame|publisher= |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nFrancis shared a personal story on Brisbane radio on the impact of her sister's death.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.abc.net.au/queensland/2013/03/the-view-from-brisbane-wendy-francis.html?site=brisbane&program=612_breakfast|title=The View From Brisbane - Wendy Francis |author=Levingston, Rebecca |date=25 March 2013 |work=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] |publisher= |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Lobbying==\nSince 2007, Francis has run 'meet the candidate forums' for ACL in 15 to 20 Queensland electorates in each election.<ref name = \"elections\">{{cite news|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/opinion/opinion-dont-be-fooled-labor-supports-safe-schools/news-story/c787a1a091be8d7dff58c1ff16075a0c  |title=Opinion: Don\u2019t be fooled, Labor supports Safe Schools |author=Dean, Rownan|date=13 November 2017|work=Courier Mail|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August 2010 Francis tweeted \"Children in homosexual relationships are subject to emotional abuse. Legitimising gay marriage is like legalising child abuse.\"  Francis later deleted the tweet but stood by her comments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/family-first-candidate-wendy-francis-stands-by-gay--slur-on-twitter-20100809-11s5c.html|title=Family First candidate Wendy Francis stands by gay slur on Twitter|last=Grubb|first=Ben|date=2010-08-09|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n\nDuring April 2013, Francis lobbied against government subsidies for the abortion drug [[Mifepristone|RU486]] saying, \"Women facing unsupported pregnancies should be offered real support - not a chemical which is harmful to both them and their unborn child.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-national/ru486-drug-wont-lead-to-more-abortions-20130426-2iizk.html | title=RU486 drug 'won't lead to more abortions' |author=Bennet, Adam |date=26 April 2013|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |publisher= |accessdate=5 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nFrancis has argued for [[Billboard|outdoor advertising]] to be \u2018[[Australian Classification Board|G-rated]]\u2019.<ref name=\"Background\"/> She organised ACL members to protest against bus shelter billboards - where as Francis said, \"children are waiting for the school bus\" - promoting [[safe sex]], which featured a fully clothed, hugging, gay couple holding an unopened condom packet.   Francis was criticised due to her campaign not mentioning any affiliation with the ACL, and for describing the image as an act of foreplay.<ref name=\"herald\">{{cite web |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/more-news/hiv-ads-pulled-from-brisbane-bus-shelters/story-fn7x8me2-1226067288044 |title=Adshel reinstates safe sex ad after removal sparked online backlash |author= |date=1 June 2011 |work=[[Herald Sun]] |publisher= |accessdate=1 June 2011}}</ref> A Queensland Parliament committee conducted a public hearing where Francis argued that all billboards should be \u2018G-rated\u2019.  The  committee subsequently recommended a tougher approach to sexually explicit outdoor advertising.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/new-laws-may-crack-down-on-sexually-explicit-billboards/story-fnihsrf2-1226815309185|title=New laws may crack down on sexually explicit billboards|first=Robyn|last=Ironside|date=1 February 2014|publisher=[[The Courier Mail]]|accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013 after a billboard was erected in [[Kings Cross, New South Wales]], Francis lobbied to have it removed.  The billboard displayed a fictionalised UK prime minister having sex with a pig. Francis said children should not have to see an adult image like this.  The billboard was subsequently taken down.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-05-02/christian-lobby-wants-foxtel-fined-over-bestiality-billboard/4664168|title='Christian lobby urges fines for bestiality billboard |author= |date=2 May 2013 |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC]]|publisher= |accessdate=3 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013 a ruling was made against the owners of a billboard by the [[Advertising Standards Bureau (Australia)|Advertising Standards Bureau]] (ASB).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mumbrella.com.au/ad-watchdog-bans-strip-club-poster-may-show-nipple-176191  |title=Ad watchdog bans strip club poster because it may show nipple |date=3 September 2013|work=Mumbrella|accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref> The ASB said it presented women, \"in a manner that was subservient and degrading\".  The owners said they would comply with the ruling.   With the billboard remaining in place in August 2015, Francis said that self-regulation is not working.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.townsvillebulletin.com.au/news/townsville/watchdog-powerless-to-remove-raunchy-billboard/story-fnjfzsax-1227481044699  |title=Watchdog powerless to remove raunchy billboard |author=Healy, Samantha|date=13 August 2015|work=Townsville Bulletin|accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrancis has campaigned against the offensive slogans painted on the sides of [[Wicked Campers|Wicked Camper]] vans.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/07/15/christian-lobby-sees-red-over-wicked-vans  |title=Christian lobby sees red over Wicked vans |accessdate=29 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-11-17/wicked-campers-with-'vile'-slogans-to-be-outlawed-in-tasmania/8033548  |title=Wicked Campers with 'vile and appalling' slogans to be outlawed in Tasmania |accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref>  Francis has similarly campaigned against a series of ads for shoes which incorporate naked models.  The promoters say their ads are a \"celebration of sexual expression\" and are designed to \"target a younger audience\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/fashion/designers/volley-hits-back-at-australian-christian-lobbys-homophobic-response-to-ad-campaign/news-story/36c69007512fc2d2696ff22f53ddc948  |title=Volley hits back at Australian Christian Lobby\u2019s \u2018homophobic\u2019 response to ad campaign |author=Sullivan, Rebecca|date=18 January 2017|work=|accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nFrancis received abuse over her support of changes in surrogacy laws to exclude same sex couples and single people.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/christian-lobbyist-weathers-barrage-of-abuse-20120624-20w5e.html|title=Christian lobbyist weathers barrage of abuse |author=Bridie, Jabour |date=24 June 2012|work=[[The Brisbane Times]] |publisher= |accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Francis lodged a petition with the [[Parliament of Queensland|Queensland parliament]] complaining about the [[Safe Schools Coalition Australia|Safe Schools program]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/australian-christian-lobby-slams-safe-schools-antibullying-program-20151103-gkq6gr.html  |title=Australian Christian Lobby slams Safe Schools anti-bullying program | author=Partridge, Emma|date=4 November 2015|work=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref> The petition incorporated wording from a Safe Schools student resource, ''OMG I\u2019m [[Queer]]'', intended for children aged 11 and up.  However the Clerk of the Parliament would not permit the wording on Queensland parliament\u2019s website because of the \"intemperate\" language.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/opinion/columnists/angela-shanahan/parents-are-the-best-judge-of-their-kids-sex-education-needs/news-story/a4735e9b23790a3769ac99d97d656253  |title=Parents are the best judge of their kids\u2019 sex education needs |author=Shanahan, Angela|date=27 February 2016|work=The Australian|accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref>  The 10,891-signature, petition was subsequently tabled with the \"intemperate\" wording censored.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/apps/Epetitions/ClosedEpetition.aspx?PetNum=2429  |title= Cease Safe Schools roll out in Queensland schools |date= 13 October 2015|accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref>  While the [[Annastacia Palaszczuk|Palaszczuk]] government has said that it does not have plans to introduce the Safe Schools program in Queensland, Francis is concerned that that could be reintroduced in some other form.<ref name = \"elections\"/><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/queensland-election/labor-plotting-to-revive-safe-schools-plan-says-christian-lobby/news-story/4b04d35a57a6a1b571b325b2f0daa4de |title=Queensland election: Labor plotting to revive Safe Schools plan, says Christian lobby |author=Urban, Rebecca|date=|work=The Australian|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref>  Francis has said that she supported anti-bullying programs, but the Safe Schools Coalition goes \"way beyond that\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.buzzfeed.com/lanesainty/this-is-why-the-australian-christian-lobby-is-talking-about |title= A Christian Group Is Up In Arms About Chest Binding And Here's Why|work =[[BuzzFeedNews]]| author=Sainty, Lane|date=13 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFrancis has campaigned against the liberalisation of abortion laws in Queensland.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/fact-and-reason-needed-in-abortion-debate-trad-20160625-gprrkn.html  |title='Fact and reason' needed in abortion debate |author=Remeikis, Amy|date=25 June 2016|work=Brisbane Times|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://catholicleader.com.au/news/pro-life-groups-urge-supporters-to-sign-petition-to-say-no-to-queensland-abortion-reforms-before-bills-are-debated-next-year  |title=Pro-life groups urge supporters to sign petition to say no to Queensland abortion reforms before Bills are debated next year |author=Bowning, Mark|date=8 December 2016|work=Catholic Leader|accessdate=30 December 2016}}</ref> In lobbying against 'gender selection', Francis has said that eliminating human life in its early stages for being the wrong sex, is sex discrimination.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/gender-selection-family-balancing-or-vanity-parenting/news-story/88a2b43382d09c1df6e92b445c4c8a05  |title=Gender selection: Family balancing or vanity parenting? |author=Ambrose, Margaret|date=25 November 2016|work=Herald Sun|accessdate=3 December 2016}}</ref>  Francis has said that for Australian to use its foreign aid program to finance abortion in developing countries. which are culturally opposed to abortion, is a form of \"colonialism\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/australian-christian-lobby-urges-turnbull-government-to-copy-donald-trumps-foreign-aid-abortion-ban-20170314-guxpra.html  |title=Australian Christian Lobby urges Turnbull government to copy Donald Trump's foreign aid abortion ban }}</ref>\n\nFrancis also supports the 'Nordic' model of prostitution legalisation - which has been described as the world\u2019s first human rights/women\u2019s rights-based legal model of prostitution legislation. The Nordic Approach does not criminalise the prostitute, but rather it criminalises the buyer \u2014 addressing the demand for prostitution, and importantly also provides women with exit strategies. Within four years of the law being implemented, the number of women involved in prostitution in Sweden halved.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/opinion/wendy-francis-south-australia-can-lead-australia-by-introducing-worlds-most-uptodate-prostitution-legislation/news-story/b20bf6eb4d752f5faa89593289ec7045|title=SA has chance to reform sex industry|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref>\n\nIn response to children being taught that they can choose their gender, Francis has had two books published entitled, \"What are little boys made of?\" and \"What are little girls made of?\" describing how a child\u2019s biological sex determines whether they are a boy or a girl, with each sex having specific [[XY sex-determination system|X or Y chromosomes]].  Francis does not ignore the reality of children born with [[intersex]] conditions which, whilst rare, account for a number of genetic or developmental situations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.qbmagazine.org.au/what-are-little-boys-and-girls-made-of/  |title=What are little Boys and Girls Made of? |work =QB Magazine| date=24 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Centre for Human Dignity===\nFrancis heads the 'Centre for Human Dignity', which was established in 2017 by ACL<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acl.org.au/centre_for_human_dignity_united_against_sexual_exploitation  |title= Centre For Human Dignity - United Against Sexual Exploitation|author=|date=|work=Australian Christian Lobby|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref> to advocate for rights and freedoms, particularly for vulnerable children and to stand against all forms of sexual exploitation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centreforhumandignity.org.au/  |title=Centre for Human Dignity  |work=Centre for Human Dignity|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n===Books===\n* ''What are little girls made of?  What are little boys made of?'', [[Connor Court Publishing]], 2019, {{ISBN|9781925826357}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.connorcourtpublishing.com.au/What-are-little-girls-made-of-What-are-little-boys-made-of-As-a-set_p_254.html  |title=What are little girls made of?  What are little boys made of? |work =[[Connor Court Publishing]]| author=Francis, Wendy|date=May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Opinion article===\n* ''Freedom \u2013 Australia\u2019s Most Endangered Liberty'', [[Vision Christian Radio]], 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vision.org.au/radio/2017/10/19/freedom-australias-most-endangered-liberty-wendy-francis/  |title=FREEDOM \u2013 Australia\u2019s Most Endangered Liberty \u2013 Wendy Francis |work =[[Vision Christian Radio]]| author=Francis, Wendy|date=19 October 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Australia}}\n* [[Abortion in Australia]]\n* [[Australian Catholic Bishops' Conference]]\n* [[Australian Marriage Law Postal Survey]]\n* [[Christianity in Australia]]\n* [[Coalition for Marriage (Australia)]]\n* [[Euthanasia in Australia]]\n* [[FamilyVoice Australia]]\n* [[Human rights in Australia]]\n* [[Marriage Alliance]]\n* [[Marriage in Australia]]\n* [[National Organization for Marriage]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Francis, Wendy}}\n[[Category:Australian Christians]]\n[[Category:Australian lobbyists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "14.2.64.121", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wendy_Francis"}
{"title_page": "Solar power in India", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2012}}\n[[File:India GHI mid-size-map 156x194mm-300dpi v20191015.png|thumb|Solar potential of India]]\n'''Solar power in India''' is a fast developing industry. The country's solar installed capacity reached 34.404 GW as of 29 February 2020.<ref name=ach>{{cite news|title=Physical Progress (Achievements)|url=https://mnre.gov.in/the-ministry/physical-progress|accessdate=18 July 2019|publisher=Ministry of New & Renewable Energy}}</ref> India has the lowest capital cost per MW globally to install [[solar power]] plants.<ref>{{cite news|title=India becomes lowest-cost producer of solar power |url=https://energy.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/renewable/india-becomes-lowest-cost-producer-of-solar-power/69565769|accessdate=1 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Race Heats Up For Title Of Cheapest Solar Energy In The World|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dominicdudley/2019/10/17/cheapest-solar-energy-in-the-world/#517f472a4772|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref>    \n\nThe Indian government had an initial target of 20 GW capacity for 2022, which was achieved four years ahead of schedule.<ref name=\"bsInJan2018\" /><ref name=\"ToiOnSolarJan2018\" /><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1007/s40032-018-0454-6|title = Solar Energy a Path to India's Prosperity| journal=Journal of the Institution of Engineers (India): Series C|volume = 100|issue = 3|pages = 539\u2013546|year = 2018|last1 = Chandra|first1 = Yogender Pal| last2=Singh| first2=Arashdeep| last3=Kannojiya| first3=Vikas| last4=Kesari| first4=J. P.}}</ref> In 2015 the target was raised to 100 GW of solar capacity (including 40 GW from [[rooftop solar]]) by 2022, targeting an investment of {{USD}}100 billion.<ref>[http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/government-looking-at-100-000-mw-solar-power-by-2022-114111701373_1.html Government looking at 100,000 MW solar power by 2022]</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/01/02/india-solar-idUSL3N0UG13H20150102 |title=India's Modi raises solar investment target to $100 bln by 2022 |date=2015-01-02 |publisher=Reuters |author=Krishna N. Das |accessdate=2015-01-02}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pv-tech.org/news/india_releases_individual_state_targets_for_40gw_rooftop_solar_by_2022 |title=India releases state targets for 40GW rooftop solar by 2022 |access-date=2016-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mnre.gov.in/file-manager/UserFiles/Tentative-State-wise-break-up-of-Renewable-Power-by-2022.pdf |title=State-wise break-up of solar power target by the year 2022 |access-date=11 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"renewableET201607182\">{{Cite news |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/energy/power/government-working-to-double-generation-target-from-solar-parks/articleshow/53268569.cms |title=Government working to double generation target from solar parks |date=2016-07-18 |publisher=Economic Times |format= |accessdate=2016-07-18|newspaper=The Economic Times }}</ref> India has established nearly 42 solar parks to make land available to the promoters of solar plants.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mnre.gov.in/sites/default/files/uploads/18.%20List%20of%20Solar%20Parks%20as%20on%2031-05-2019.docx |title=List of solar parks in India |accessdate=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIndia expanded its solar-generation capacity 8 times from 2,650 MW on 26 May 2014 to over 20 GW as on 31 January 2018.<ref name=\"bsInJan2018\">{{cite web | url=http://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/india-achieves-20-gw-solar-capacity-goal-4-years-ahead-deadline/story/269266.html |title=Achieving 2022 target four years ahead of schedule |accessdate=2018-02-04}}</ref><ref name=\"ToiOnSolarJan2018\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/environment/developmental-issues/india-hits-20gw-solar-capacity-milestone/articleshow/62715512.cms|title=India hits 20 GW solar capacity milestone|accessdate=4 February 2018}}</ref> \nThe country added 3 GW of solar capacity in 2015\u20132016, 5 GW in 2016\u20132017 and over 10 GW in 2017\u20132018, with the average current price of solar electricity dropping to 18% below the average price of its coal-fired counterpart.<ref name=pg>{{cite news |title=India's solar capacity to cross 20GW in next 15 months: Piyush Goyal |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/energy/power/indias-solar-energy-capacity-expanded-by-record-5525-mw/articleshow/58037873.cms |website=Economic Times |accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.livemint.com/Industry/dUQtwINipgqq4xT0feuxqJ/USs-Paris-climate-deal-exit-may-lower-Indias-solar-power-t.html |title=US's Paris climate deal exit may lower India's solar power tariffs further |accessdate=2017-06-16 }}</ref><ref name=\"bbcParisClimateDeal\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-40120770 |title=Five effects of a US pull-out from Paris climate deal |last=McGrath |first=Matt |publisher=BBC |date=2017-06-01 |accessdate=2017-06-01 |format= }}</ref>. By the end of September 2019, India has installed more than 82,580 MW of renewable energy capacity with around 31,150 MW of capacity under various stages of installation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pib.gov.in/newsite/pmreleases.aspx?mincode=28|title=PIB|website=pib.gov.in|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n\nRooftop solar power accounts for 2.1 GW, of which 70% is industrial or commercial.<ref name=srtgw1>{{cite news|url=https://www.downtoearth.org.in/news/energy/renewable-energy-in-india-why-rooftop-remains-the-most-untapped-solar-source-62873|title= Renewable energy in India: why rooftop remains the most untapped solar source|accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> \nIn addition to its large-scale grid-connected solar photovoltaic (PV) initiative, India is developing off-grid solar power for local energy needs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/energy/power/solar-water-pumps-can-help-india-surpass-100-gw-target-report/articleshow/65214158.cms|title=Solar water pumps can help India surpass 100 GW target: Report |accessdate= 2 August 2017}}</ref> \nSolar products have increasingly helped to meet rural needs; by the end of 2015 just under one million [[solar lantern]]s were sold in the country, reducing the need for kerosene.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=http://mnre.gov.in/file-manager/annual-report/2015-2016/EN/Chapter%201/chapter_1.htm |title=Ministry of New and Renewable Energy, Annual Report 2015-2016 |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date=2017-04-21}}</ref> \nThat year, 118,700 solar home lighting systems were installed and 46,655 solar street lighting installations were provided under a national program;<ref name=\":0\" /> just over 1.4 million [[solar cooker]]s were distributed in India.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe [[International Solar Alliance]] (ISA), proposed by India as a founder member, is headquartered in India.\n\n==National solar potential==\n{{anchor|Solar resources}}\nWith about 300 clear and sunny days in a year, the calculated [[solar energy]] incidence on India's land area is about 5000 trillion [[kilowatt-hour]]s (kWh) per year (or 5 [[Exa-|E]]Wh/yr).<ref name=\"SPSEPRIE\">{{cite journal |last1=Muneer |first1=T. |last2=Asif |first2=M. |last3=Munawwar |first3=S. |doi=10.1016/j.rser.2004.03.004 |title=Sustainable production of solar electricity with particular reference to the Indian economy |journal=Renewable and Sustainable Energy Reviews |volume=9 |issue=5 |pages=444 |year=2005 |pmid= |pmc=}} (publication archived in ScienceDirect, needs subscription or access via university)</ref><ref name=\"mnreSolar\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mnre.gov.in/schemes/grid-connected/solar/ |title=Solar |publisher=Ministry of New and Renewable Energy, Govt. of India |accessdate=2014-02-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225160014/http://www.mnre.gov.in/schemes/grid-connected/solar/ |archive-date=25 February 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The solar energy available in a single year exceeds the possible energy output of all of the [[fossil fuel]] energy reserves in India. The daily average solar-power-plant generation capacity in India is 0.20 kWh per m<sup>2</sup> of used land area, equivalent to 1400\u20131800 peak (rated) capacity operating hours in a year with available, commercially-proven technology.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://photovoltaic-software.com/PV-solar-energy-calculation.php  |title=How to calculate the annual solar energy output of a photovoltaic system? |accessdate=2017-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pveducation.org/pvcdrom/modules/mismatch-effects  |title=Comprehensive technical data of PV modules |accessdate=2015-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://mercomindia.com/mono-perc-modules-india/  |title=Mono PERC Solar Modules are Coming to India; It is Just a Matter of When |accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Installations by region==\n\n===Installated cumulative national and state-wise capacity===\n\n{{Bar graph\n| title       = Installed solar PV on 31 March<ref name=year>{{cite web|url=https://mnre.gov.in/img/documents/uploads/0ce0bba7b9f24b32aed4d89265d6b067.pdf|title= Page 15, Solar power - Overview |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n| float       = right\n| bar_width   = 24\n| width_units = em\n| data_max    = 30000\n| label_type  = Year\n| data_type   = Cumulative Capacity (in MW)\n| label1      = 2010\n| data1       = 161\n| label2      = 2011\n| data2       = 461\n| label3      = 2012\n| data3       = 1205\n| label4      = 2013\n| data4       = 2319\n| label5      = 2014\n| data5       = 2632\n| label6      = 2015\n| data6       = 3744\n| label7      = 2016\n| data7       = 6763\n| label8      = 2017\n| data8       = 12289\n| label9      = 2018\n| data9       = 21,651\n| label10      = 2019\n| data10       = 28,181\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|+ Ground mounted 