eflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|thehawaiibowl.com}}\n\n{{Hawaii Bowl navbox}}\n{{Bowl game navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Hawaii Bowl|*]]\n[[Category:College football bowls]]\n[[Category:American football in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:College sports in Hawaii]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the college football All-Star game|Hula Bowl}}\n{{Collegebowl\n| name               = Hawaii Bowl\n| full_name          = SoFi Hawai'i Bowl\n| nickname           = \n| defunct            =\n| logo               = HawaiiBowl.png\n| image_size         = 250px\n| caption            = \n| stadium            = [[Aloha Stadium]]\n| previous_stadiums  = \n| location           = [[Halawa, Hawaii]]\n| previous_locations = \n| years              = 2002\u2013Present\n| preceded_by        = [[Aloha Bowl]]\n| previous_tie-ins   = [[Western Athletic Conference|WAC]] (2002\u20132011)<br/>[[Conference USA|C-USA]]/[[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-10]] (2005\u20132008)<br/>C-USA (2009\u20132018)\n| conference_tie-ins = [[Mountain West Conference|MWC]] (2012\u2013present)<br/>[[American Athletic Conference|The American]] (2019\u2013present)\n| payout             = 1.2 million (2019)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collegefootballpoll.com/bowl-schedule/2019/ |title=2019 Bowl Schedule |website=collegefootballpoll.com |accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| sponsors           = [[ConAgra Foods]] (2002)<br>[[Sheraton Hotels and Resorts Hawaii]] (2003\u20132013)<br>[[SoFi]] (2018\u2013present)\n| former_names       = ConAgra Foods Hawaii Bowl (2002)<br>Sheraton Hawaii Bowl (2003\u20132013)<br>Hawaii Bowl (2014-2017)\n| prev_matchup_year  = 2018\n| prev_matchup_season= 2018\n| prev_matchup_teams = [[2018 Hawaii Rainbow Warriors football team|Hawaii]] vs. [[2018 Louisiana Tech Bulldogs football team|Louisiana Tech]]<br>\n| prev_matchup_score = Louisiana Tech 31\u201314\n| next_matchup_year  = 2019\n| next_matchup_season= 2019\n| next_matchup_teams = [[2019 BYU Cougars football team|BYU]] vs. [[2019 Hawaii Rainbow Warriors football team|Hawaii]]\n| next_matchup_date  = Hawaii 38\u201334\n}}\nThe '''Hawai\u02bbi Bowl''' is a [[college football]] [[bowl game]] that has been played annually at [[Aloha Stadium]] in [[Honolulu, Hawaii]], since 2002. The bowl is one of the post-season contests run by [[ESPN Events]]. Since 2018, the game has been sponsored by the personal finance company [[SoFi]] and officially known as the ''SoFi Hawai'i Bowl''. Previous sponsors include [[ConAgra Foods]] (2002) and [[Sheraton Hotels and Resorts Hawaii]] (2003\u20132013).\n\nTypically played on or near [[Christmas Eve]], the bowl normally features a team from the [[Mountain West Conference]], playing a team from either the [[American Athletic Conference]] or [[Conference USA]]. For practical and logistical reasons, the Mountain West bid is automatically awarded to the [[Hawaii Rainbow Warriors football|Hawaii Rainbow Warriors]] if the team is [[bowl-eligible]], and was not selected to play in a [[New Year's Six]] (or previously [[Bowl Championship Series|BCS]]) bowl game. This means that the Rainbow Warriors do not have to travel to the [[Contiguous United States|mainland]] for a bowl game unless it is of significant importance. As a result of this practice, they have also made the most appearances in the game, at nine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/college-football/2016/12/24/14073110/hawaii-bowl-2016-game-time-tv-history|title=Why Hawaii is in the Hawaii Bowl so much|last=Kirshner|first=Alex|date=2016-12-24|website=SBNation.com|access-date=2018-12-23}}</ref>\n\n==Bowl games in Hawaii==\nThe Hawaii Bowl is not affiliated with other bowl games previously staged in Hawaii: the [[Poi Bowl]] (1936\u20131939), [[Pineapple Bowl]] (1940\u20131941, 1947\u20131952), [[Aloha Bowl]] (1982\u20132000), and [[Oahu Bowl]] (1998\u20132000), or the [[Hula Bowl]] all-star game (1960\u20132008, and resuming in 2020). While the Aloha Bowl tried to move to [[San Francisco]], [[California]], and was decertified by the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]], the Oahu Bowl was moved to [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], and was held for two years as the [[Seattle Bowl]] before losing certification in 2002.\n\n==Game history==\nIn its first year, the Hawai'i Bowl was sponsored by [[ConAgra Foods, Inc.|ConAgra Foods]]. The following year, [[Sheraton Hotels and Resorts Hawaii]] assumed sponsorship; the game's full name was changed to the '''Sheraton Hawai'i Bowl''' until Sheraton declined to renew sponsorship in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2014/05/09/sheraton-hotels-resorts-drops-title-sponsorship-of.html?iana=ind_sports |title=Sheraton Hotels & Resorts drops title sponsorship of Hawaii Bowl college football game}}</ref>  In 2018, [[SoFi]] signed on as title sponsor of the game which is officially known as the '''SoFi Hawai'i Bowl'''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehawaiibowl.com/hawaii-bowl-names-sofi-as-new-title-sponsor/ |title=Hawai\u2018i Bowl Names SoFi As New Title Sponsor |accessdate=November 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe current Mountain West tie-in was held by the [[Western Athletic Conference]] (WAC) until 2012, when the WAC ceased sponsoring college football, and Hawaii moved to the Mountain West.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/7376711/mountain-west-conference-aligns-sheraton-hawaii-bowl-starting-2012|title=Mountain West Conference aligns with Sheraton Hawaii Bowl starting in 2012|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe first two editions were played on the Aloha Bowl's traditional Christmas Day date, but ESPN's [[NBA on ESPN|acquisition of NBA rights]] came with the league's [[National Basketball Association Christmas games|Christmas Day games]], thus the game moved to [[Christmas Eve]] after 2004 in most years.\n\nThe [[2005 Hawai'i Bowl|2005]] appearance of the [[UCF Knights football|UCF Knights]] at the Hawaii Bowl was the first ever bowl game in that school's history. In [[2006 Hawai'i Bowl|2006]], the Pac-10 replaced [[Conference USA]] (C-USA) as the WAC's opposition, with C-USA as an alternate. Since Christmas Eve fell on a Monday in [[2007 Hawai'i Bowl|2007]], the game was scheduled for the night prior (December 23) to avoid a conflict with ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' (also on ESPN). In [[2008 Hawai'i Bowl|2008]], the bowl organizers selected [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame]] as an [[at-large bid]], marking the first time an [[NCAA Division I FBS independent schools|independent]] played in the contest. C-USA again became a primary tie-in starting in [[2009 Hawai'i Bowl|2009]]. The [[2011 Hawai'i Bowl|2011]] game featured the C-USA champion for the first time, as [[Southern Mississippi Golden Eagles football|Southern Mississippi]] played instead of going to the [[Liberty Bowl]], where the C-USA champion typically plays. The bowl featured the Mountain West champion for the first time in [[2008 Hawai'i Bowl|2015]], as [[San Diego State Aztecs football|San Diego State]] played instead of going to the [[Las Vegas Bowl]], where the Mountain West champion typically plays.\n\nBetween 2002 and 2018, C-USA sent a team to the bowl 12 times, registering an 8\u20134 record. In 2019, the [[American Athletic Conference]] (The American) superseded C-USA as the primary tie-in to face a Mountain West team (or independent [[BYU Cougars football|BYU]]).<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.thehawaiibowl.com/2019-sofi-hawaii-bowl-return-dec-24/ |title=2019 SoFi Hawai\u2018I Bowl to Return to Dec. 24 |website=thehawaiibowl.com |date=May 23, 2019 |accessdate=May 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Tenth Anniversary Team (2011)===\nTo celebrate the tenth anniversary of the Hawai'i Bowl, the ''[[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]]'', in conjunction with the bowl game, allowed fans to vote on a tenth anniversary team. Nine players were selected by a public vote, and an additional seven players were picked by a panel of sportswriters and organizers. The team was announced on December 16, 2011.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n! style=\"background:#00A7CF; color:#ffffff; border: 2px solid #7FBE41;\" colspan=\"4\" | Ten Year Anniversary Team&nbsp;\n|-\n! Year !! Player !! College !! Performance\n|-\n| [[2002 Hawaii Bowl|2002]] || Justin Colbert || [[2002 Hawaii Warriors football team|Hawaii]] || 9 catches for 158 yards and 2 TD's.\n|-\n| [[2003 Hawaii Bowl|2003]] || [[Timmy Chang]] <br>[[Jackie Battle]]|| [[2003 Hawaii Warriors football team|Hawaii]]<br>[[Houston Cougars football|Houston]] || 26 for 42, 475 yards, 5 TD's passing.<br>19 carries for 124 yards and 3 TD's.\n|-\n| [[2004 Hawaii Bowl|2004]] || [[Chad Owens]]  || [[2004 Hawaii Warriors football team|Hawaii]] || 8 catches for 114 yards, 2 TD's.<br>5 punt returns for 90 yards and a TD.\n|-\n| [[2005 Hawaii Bowl|2005]] || Caleb Spencer<br>[[Brandon Marshall]] || [[Nevada Wolfpack football|Nevada]]<br>[[UCF Knights football|UCF]]|| 11 receptions for 114 yards.<br>11 receptions for 210 yards and 3 TD's.\n|-\n| [[2006 Hawaii Bowl|2006]] || [[Colt Brennan]]<br>[[Jason Rivers (American football)|Jason Rivers]] || [[2006 Hawaii Warriors football team|Hawaii]]<br>[[2006 Hawaii Warriors football team|Hawaii]] || 33 for 42, 559 yards and 5 TD's.<br>14 receptions for 308 yards and 2 TD's.\n|-\n| [[2007 Hawaii Bowl|2007]] || [[Chris Johnson (running back)|Chris Johnson]] || [[2007 East Carolina Pirates football team|East Carolina]] || 408 all purpose yards, 2 TD's.\n|-\n| [[2008 Hawaii Bowl|2008]] || [[Golden Tate]]<br>[[Jimmy Clausen]]<br>Aaron Bain  || [[2008 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]]<br>[[2008 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]]<br>[[2008 Hawaii Warriors football team|Hawaii]] || 6 receptions for 177 yards and 3 TD's.<br>22 for 26, 401 yards and 5TD's<br>8 receptions for 109 yards and 2 TD's.\n\n|-\n| [[2009 Hawaii Bowl|2009]] || [[Kyle Padron