, Southern Mississippi vs. Nevada<br>Chase Hover, SMU vs. Fresno State || <br>2011<br>2012\n|}\n\n==Media coverage==\n{{main|List of Hawaii Bowl broadcasters}}\nThe bowl has been televised on [[ESPN]] since its inception.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|thehawaiibowl.com}}\n\n{{Hawaii Bowl navbox}}\n{{Bowl game navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Hawaii Bowl|*]]\n[[Category:College football bowls]]\n[[Category:American football in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:College sports in Hawaii]]\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkCole McDonaldusingFind link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hawaii_Bowl"}
{"title_page": "Mark Aubry", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Mark Aubry\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1954|11|24}}\n| birth_place  = [[Noranda, Quebec]], Canada\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  = \n| alma_mater   = [[University of Ottawa]]\n| occupation   = [[Physician]]\n| years_active = 1981\u2013present \n| employer     = [[Ottawa Senators]] \n| known_for    = [[Sports medicine]] specialist, and [[Chief Medical Officer]] of the [[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] and [[Hockey Canada]]\n| awards       = [[Paul Loicq Award]], Dr. [[Tom Pashby]] sports safety award \n}}\n\n'''Mark John Aubry''' (born November 24, 1954) is a Canadian [[physician]] and [[sports medicine]] specialist. He is the team physician for the [[Ottawa Senators]], and serves as the [[Chief Medical Officer]] of both the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]], and [[Hockey Canada]]. He researches and lectures on [[concussion]]s, plays a leadership role for safety in sport, and is an injury prevention activist in minor ice hockey. He is a recipient of the [[Paul Loicq Award]] for his international work, and the Dr. [[Tom Pashby]] sports safety award for Canada.\n\n==Early life==\nAubry was born November 24, 1954, in [[Noranda, Quebec]],<ref name=\"IIHF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iihf.com/home-of-hockey/news/iihf-hof-2014/|title=Paul Loicq Award: Dr Mark Aubry (CAN)|date=2014|website=IIHF|access-date=July 31, 2018}}</ref> and learned to speak both English and French.<ref name=\"cpso\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cpso.on.ca/DoctorDetails/Aubry-Mark-John/0028044-32867|title=Aubry, Mark John (CPSO#: 32867)|website=[[College of Physicians and Surgeons of Ontario]]|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> He attended [[Merivale High School]], and played hockey, football and baseball at school.<ref name=\"MayorsCup\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insideottawavalley.com/community-story/3803201-fury-s-zito-picked-for-top-male-coach-award/|title=Fury's Zito picked for top male coach award|date=January 21, 2011|website=InsideOttawaValley.com|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> Aubry began playing [[junior ice hockey]] as a [[Centre (ice hockey)|centreman]]; he is listed at 6 feet tall, and 180 pounds, for the [[Rockland Nationals|Ottawa M and W Rangers]] in the [[Central Canada Hockey League]] during the 1971\u201372 season.<ref name=\"hockeydb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=72733|title=Mark Aubry hockey statistics and profile|website=hockeydb|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> During the 1972\u201373 season, he was coached by future [[IIHF Hall of Fame]] inductee, [[Derek Holmes (ice hockey)|Derek Holmes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/leagues/seasons/teams/0032181973.html|title=Ottawa M and W Rangers 1972&ndash;73 roster and scoring statistics|website=hockeydb.com|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> Aubry won the most valuable player award and the sportsmanship award in the 1972\u201373 season with the Rangers, and won the sportsmanship award again in the 1973\u201374 season.<ref name=\"CCHL\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thecchl.ca/season-award-archives|title=Season Award Archives|website=Central Canada Hockey League|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> He then played for the [[Ottawa Gee-Gees]] during the 1974&ndash;75 and 1975&ndash;76 seasons,<ref name=\"hockeydb\" /><ref name=\"uottawa\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uottawa.ca/archives/sites/www.uottawa.ca.archives/files/hockey.pdf|title=Historique du hockey \u00e0 l'Universit\u00e9 d'Ottawa|language=french|website=University of Ottawa archives|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> while earning his medical degree.<ref name=\"dr-aubry\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeycanada.ca/en-ca/exclusive/quebec-hockey-summit/home/attendees/speakers/mark-aubry|title=Doctor Mark Aubry|website=Hockey Canada|access-date=July 31, 2018}}</ref> After playing, he worked as a trainer for the Gee-Gees.<ref name=\"MayorsCup\" />\n\n==Medical career==\nAubry graduated from the [[University of Ottawa]] in 1978.<ref name=\"cpso\" /> He established a [[family medicine]] office in [[Hull, Quebec]] on September, 18, 1981.<ref name=\"cpso\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> As of 2018, he is a director at the Ottawa Sport Medicine Centre,<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> and is a team physician for the [[Ottawa Senators]].<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/senators/team/front-office#medical-staff|title=Hockey Operations|website=Ottawa Senators|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> Aubry previously served as the team physician for the [[Ottawa 67's]] from 1996 to 2005,<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> the [[Ottawa Rough Riders]],<ref name=\"MayorsCup\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> the [[Ottawa Renegades]],<ref name=\"Renegades\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/opening-day-of-renegades-training-camp-highlighted-by-medicals-meetings-and-preparation/n-3168889|title=Opening day of Renegades training camp highlighted by medicals, meetings and preparation|date=May 28, 2005|website=OurSports Central|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> and the [[Ottawa Lynx]].<ref name=\"Pashby\" /> He was a trainer on [[minor ice hockey]] teams from 1989 to 2000, [[Chief Medical Officer]] (CMO) for the Canadian team at the [[1991 Winter Universiade]], and CMO of [[Canada at the 1992 Winter Olympics]] in [[Albertville]].<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" />\n\n===Sports medicine===\nAubry has spent significant time working in [[sports medicine]], lecturing on injury prevention, and researching [[concussion]]s and [[spinal cord]] injuries with respect to [[Checking (ice hockey)|body checking]] in ice hockey.<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /><ref name=\"Pashby\" /><ref name=\"bodycheck\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeyeasternontario.ca/docs/HC_Body_Checking_Brief_1.pdf|title=Hockey Canada\u2014Body Checking Brief|date=April 17, 2013|website=Hockey Eastern Ontario|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He helped organize three symposiums on sports concussions (2001 in [[Vienna]], 2004 in [[Prague]], and 2008 in [[Z\u00fcrich]]), to assist doctors in identifying and treating concussions.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> Aubry was one of the physicians consulted for the 2011 report ''Brain Injury Guide for Youth'',<ref name=\"Kutcher\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ontarioshores.ca/UserFiles/Servers/Server_6/File/PDFs/bi_teen_guide_4.pdf|title=Brain Injury Guide for Youth|last=Kutcher|first=Stan|date=2011|page=3|website=Ontario Shores|publisher=Teenmentalhealth.org|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> and was one of the medical experts that helped write the module ''Making Head Way in Sport'' released in 2014, for the Coaching Association of Canada to educate on when it is okay to return to play.<ref name=\"CAC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.coach.ca/making-head-way-in-sport-elearning-module-is-now-available-at-no-charge-p156794|title=Making Head Way in Sport eLearning module is now available at no charge|date=July 17, 2014|website=Coaching Association of Canada|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> Aubry has also spoken against focusing too much on one sport at a young age, as it has not only \"taken the fun out of it\", but also has physical and cultural risks in not developing the person.<ref name=\"Scanlan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/ottawa-citizen/20170322/281479276237544|title=Can sports be fun again?|last=Scanlan|first=Wayne|date=March 22, 2017|website=PressReader.com|publisher=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|title=World Hockey Summit|quote=\"We\u2019re exposing these kids to an increased risk of injury at an age where I think we should still be talking about skill development and having fun.\"|source=&mdash;''Mark Aubry'', 2010<ref name=\"Fitz-Gerald\" /><ref name=\"TheHockeyNews\" /><ref name=\"sportsnet\" />|width=27.5%|align=right}}\n\nAt the 2010 [[World Hockey Summit]], a joint project hosted by the National Hockey League, the [[National Hockey League Players' Association]], Hockey Canada, [[USA Hockey]], the IIHF, and the [[Canadian Hockey League]],<ref name=\"NHLPA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nhlpa.com/news/1-13651/whos-who-of-hockey-to-gather-for-world-hockey-summit|title=Who's Who of Hockey To Gather for World Hockey Summit|date=July 29, 2010|website=National Hockey League Players Association|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> Aubry called for raising the minimum age for body checking to 13 or 14 and eliminating hits from behind altogether.<ref name=\"Fitz-Gerald\" /><ref name=\"TheHockeyNews\" /> Based on his research and experience, he argued that children should be developing skills instead, as they are the most vulnerable to injury due to height and weight differences; he cited research which highlights risks of long-term effects for athletes who have had multiple concussions, specifically younger hockey players.<ref name=\"Fitz-Gerald\">{{cite news|title=Delay body checks till 13, 14, doc says|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|last1=Fitz-Gerald|first1=Sean|last2=Strong|first2=Gregory|date=August 25, 2010|page=24|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-25-2010-776136/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref name=\"TheHockeyNews\">{{cite web|url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/medical-doctor-nhl-coach-say-kids-shouldnt-learn-to-hit-until-later-teen-years|title=Medical doctor, NHL coach say kids shouldn\u2019t learn to hit until later teen years|date=August 24, 2010|website=TheHockeyNews|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"citizen\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/ottawa-citizen/20101107/282445640437138|title=HEADS-UP FOR HOCKEY: No agreement on how to fix concussions in youth sport|last=Scanlan|first=Wayne|date=November 7, 2010|via=PressReader|newspaper=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> Aubry called for instructing players that a body check is a way of separating an opponent from the puck, rather than continuing the perception of hockey as a rough sport where putting an opposing player through the boards is considered part of the game,<ref name=\"citizen\" /> given that no safety equipment could prevent serious injuries such as the [[Ronny Keller]] incident resulting in paraplegia.<ref name=\"B\u00e9land\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/sports/hockey/201303/07/01-4628664-un-joueur-suisse-paralyse-la-pire-blessure-au-hockey.php|title=Un joueur suisse paralys\u00e9: La pire blessure au hockey|language=French||last=B\u00e9land|first=Gabriel|date=March 7, 2013|website=La Presse|access-date=August 1, 2018}}</ref> Aubry has also testified before the [[Canadian International Trade Tribunal]] as an expert witness on the safety of hockey equipment.<ref name=\"CITT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.citt.gc.ca/en/file/1116/download%3Ftoken%3DvoNulTlm|title=Appeal No. AP-96-007|date=August 29, 1997|website=Canadian International Trade Tribunal|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAubry stated that awareness on the long-term effects of concussions increased partially because of the injuries to [[Sidney Crosby]], but noted that physicians in the [[National Hockey League]] still disagree on when players are healthy enough to return to play.<ref name=\"CMAJ\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cmaj.ca/content/cmaj/early/2011/12/19/cmaj.109-4080.full.pdf|title=Physicians must be brought up to speed on concussion risks|last=Fallis|first=Jordan|date=December 19, 2011|website=Canadian Medical Association Journal|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He was one of the authors in the 2017 report ''Can visible signs predict concussion diagnosis in the National Hockey League?''<ref name=\"BJSM\">{{cite web|url=https://bjsm.bmj.com/content/early/2017/04/04/bjsports-2016-097090.info|title=Can visible signs predict concussion diagnosis in the National Hockey League?|date=April 4, 2017|publisher=British Journal of Sports Medicine|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> He assessed Senators' player [[Clarke MacArthur]] for [[post-concussion syndrome]],<ref name=\"Clinton\">{{cite web|url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/senators-macarthur-will-need-to-pass-neuro-psych-test-in-order-to-play-again|title=Senators\u2019 MacArthur will need to pass \u2018neuro-psych test\u2019 in order to play again|last=Clinton|first=Jared|date=December 13, 2016|website=TheHockeyNews|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> and said that given MacArthur's history, it would be too risky to return to play.<ref name=\"Garrioch\">{{cite web|url=https://ottawasun.com/2017/01/20/ottawa-senators-decide-to-shut-down-clarke-macarthur-for-remainder-of-season/wcm/d1bc30e6-5496-4d2c-96a8-8245457c19c6|title=Ottawa Senators decide to shut down Clarke MacArthur for remainder of season|last=Garrioch|first=Bruce|date=January 20, 2017|website=Ottawa Sun|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> He also cited research that in-game concussion protocols need to be strictly adhered to, and reiterated the need to evaluate players at the first sign of possible concussion, rather than staying in the game.<ref name=\"Klein\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thespec.com/sports-story/4154849-researchers-call-for-safer-hockey-after-injuries-sideline-3-nhl-players-in-season-s-first-eight-days/|title=Researchers call for safer hockey after injuries sideline 3 NHL players in season\u2019s first eight days|last=Klein|first=Jeff Z.|date=October 12, 2013|website=Hamilton Spectator|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He recommends a proactive approach to ensure players do not return to play too soon, citing recent studies on the numbers of concussions in minor ice hockey, and specifically at the peewee age level when players are typically exposed to body checking for the first time.<ref name=\"sportsnet\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/hockey-summit/|title=Hockey Summit: Talk moves to injuries|date=August 24, 2010|website=Sportsnet.ca|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He also spoke at the [[Canadian Academy of Sport and Exercise Medicine]] (CASEM) conference in August 2018, to address post-concussion syndrome, and methods for diagnosis.<ref name=\"CASEM\">{{cite web|url=https://casem-acmse.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/2018-Hockey-Preliminary-Program-FINAL5-4.pdf|title=Keep Your Edge|date=August 17, 2018|pages=2,4,6|website=Canadian Academy of Sport and Exercise Medicine|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===International hockey===\nAubry has served as the CMO of the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]] (IIHF) since 1998.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"Pashby\">{{cite web|url=http://www.drpashby.ca/2006/11/dr-mark-aubry-2006-dr-tom-pashby-sports-safety-award|title=Dr. Mark Aubry \u2013 2006 Dr. Tom Pashby Sports Safety Award|date=November 18, 2006|website=Dr. Pashby Sports Safety Fund|access-date=August 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814002052/http://www.drpashby.ca/2006/11/dr-mark-aubry-2006-dr-tom-pashby-sports-safety-award|archive-date=August 14, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> He took over the CMO position from [[Wolf-Dieter Montag]], who had served in the role since 1975.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gots.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/CV_Montag.pdf|title=Wolf-Dieter Montag \u2013 Curriculum Vitae|date=19 November 2014|website=Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Orthop\u00e4disch-Traumatologische Sportmedizin|language=de|page=2}}</ref> Aubry also sits on the medical commission of the [[International Olympic Committee]].<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> In this role, he advised against international travel to [[Beijing]] for the [[2003 Women's Ice Hockey World Championships]], which was ultimately cancelled because of the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS outbreak]].<ref name=\"SARS\">{{cite news|title=Women's hockey tourney canceled because of illness|newspaper=Colorado Springs Gazette|location=Colorado Springs, Colorado|date=March 31, 2003|page=64|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-31-2003-776152/}}{{free access}}</ref> In [[ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics]], Aubry stated that the drug which [[Mattias \u00d6hlund|Mattias Ohlund]] tested positive for was contained in the medicine given to him after eye surgery, and should not be considered a doping infraction.<ref name=\"Lebrun\">{{cite news|title=Ohlund will play in Olympic games|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|last=Lebrun|first=Pierre|author-link=Pierre LeBrun|date=January 22, 2002|page=10|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-22-2002-776127/}}{{free access}}</ref> In [[ice hockey at the 2014 Winter Olympics]], Aubry stated that [[Nicklas B\u00e4ckstr\u00f6m|Nicklas Backstrom]]'s positive test for [[pseudoephedrine]] was a result of [[Cetirizine|Zyrtec-D]] taken to treat [[sinusitis]], and it should not be considered a doping infraction.<ref name=\"Carrera\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/olympics/nicklas-backstrom-fails-ioc-doping-test-misses-gold-medal-olympic-hockey-game/2014/02/23/fec67726-9cc0-11e3-8112-52fdf646027b_story.html|title=Nicklas Backstrom fails IOC doping test, misses gold medal Olympic hockey game|last1=Carrera|first1=Katie|last2=Sheinin|first2=Dave|date=February 23, 2014|website=Washington Post|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"TheLocal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.se/20140223/dreams-of-hockey-gold-sabotaged-by-ioc-sweden|title=Hockey star's doping ban 'was political'|date=February 23, 2014|website=The Local|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> Since Aubry became CMO, IIHF competitions and the Winter Olympic Games, ice hockey officials have been instructed to penalize all hits to the head, and are critiqued for any such missed calls.<ref name=\"citizen\" /> Aubry was one of the authors of the 2017 report ''Concussions in international ice hockey championships and olympic winter games between 2006 and 2015''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/320847926_Concussions_in_international_ice_hockey_championships_and_olympic_winter_games_between_2006_and_2015|title=Concussions in international ice hockey championships and olympic winter games between 2006 and 2015|date=June 2017|website=Researchgate|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> He later spoke at a CASEM conference, discussing how the faults in how the IIHF reports injuries, and the lessons to be learned.<ref name=\"CASEM\" />\n\n===Hockey Canada===\n{{quote box|title=Hockey Canada concussion seminar|quote=\"The fight in reducing concussions is global in nature and needs the help of every participant in the sport to prevent this injury through fair play, enforcement of the rules and other measures.\"|source=&mdash;''Mark Aubry'', 2010<ref name=\"Perry\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/hockey-canada-set-to-host-concussion-seminar-1.925991|title=Hockey Canada set to host concussion seminar|last=Perry|first=Rod|date=2010-11-09|website=CBC Sports|access-date=2018-08-04}}</ref>|width=27.5%|align=right}}\n\nAubry has served as the CMO of [[Hockey Canada]] since 2004,<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"Pashby\" /> assisted in developing the Hockey Canada Safety Program, and is a part the safety program committee.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" />  He pushed for Hockey Canada to adopt [[zero tolerance]] rules for hits to the head, whether accidental or not, and recommended that teams have seminars on the risks of concussions.<ref name=\"CMAJ\" /> Since he became CMO, Hockey Canada now requires team trainers to complete a course on handling concussions,<ref name=\"citizen\" /> recommends that players with concussions get a [[medical certificate]] with a doctor's permission to play,<ref name=\"CMAJ\" /> and standardized the graduated implementation of checking skills through its age levels across Canada.<ref name=\"bodycheck\" /> Aubry has also pushed for educating on ice officials for calling hitting from behind infractions, in addition to checks to the head.<ref name=\"B\u00e9land\" /> Aubry published [[Influenza A virus subtype H1N1|H1N1 influenza]] preventative guidelines prior to the 2009\u201310 hockey season,<ref name=\"H1N1\">{{cite news|title=H1N1 had an impact on teams' operations this season|newspaper=Portage La Prairie Central Plains Herald Leader|location=Portage La Prairie, Manitoba|date=February 27, 2010|page=44|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-feb-27-2010-776138/}}{{free access}}</ref> and later issued guidelines for the use of water bottles and sports drinks, to prevent the spread of contagious viruses.<ref name=\"Mittelstaedt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/hockey-canada-shuns-sharing-of-bottles/article4291274/|title=Hockey Canada shuns sharing of bottles|last=Mittelstaedt|first=Martin|date=May 1, 2018|website=The Globe and Mail|access-date=August 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nAubry was given the Dr. [[Tom Pashby]] Sports Safety Fund Award in 2006, for his research on concussions and spinal cord injuries.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> He received the Mayor's Cup in 2011, for outstanding contributions to sport in [[Ottawa]].<ref name=\"MayorsCup\" /> He was named the recipient of the [[Paul Loicq Award]] in 2014, for contributions to international ice hockey.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/dr-mark-aubry-will-receive-the-paul-loicq-award-for-contributions-to-hockey-through-research-on-spinal-injuries-and-concussions|title=Dr. Mark Aubry will receive the Paul Loicq Award for contributions to hockey through research on spinal injuries and concussions|date=April 22, 2014|website=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Paul Loicq Award}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aubry, Mark}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian physicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian physicians]]\n[[Category:Canada at the Winter Universiade]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey centres]]\n[[Category:Canadian sports physicians]]\n[[Category:Concussion activists]]\n[[Category:Hockey Canada personnel]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Quebec]]\n[[Category:International Ice Hockey Federation executives]]\n[[Category:Lecturers]]\n[[Category:Olympic team doctors]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Gee-Gees]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Lynx]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Renegades personnel]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Rough Riders personnel]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Senators executives]]\n[[Category:Paul Loicq Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Quebec]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rouyn-Noranda]]\n[[Category:University of Ottawa alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Mark Aubry\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1954|11|24}}\n| birth_place  = [[Noranda, Quebec]], Canada\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  = \n| alma_mater   = [[University of Ottawa]]\n| occupation   = [[Physician]]\n| years_active = 1981\u2013present \n| employer     = [[Ottawa Senators]] \n| known_for    = [[Sports medicine]] specialist, and [[Chief Medical Officer]] of the [[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] and [[Hockey Canada]]\n| awards       = [[Paul Loicq Award]], Dr. [[Tom Pashby]] sports safety award \n}}\n\n'''Mark John Aubry''' (born November 24, 1954) is a Canadian [[physician]] and [[sports medicine]] specialist. He is the team physician for the [[Ottawa Senators]], and serves as the [[Chief Medical Officer]] of both the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]], and [[Hockey Canada]]. He researches and lectures on [[concussion]]s, plays a leadership role for safety in sport, and is an injury prevention activist in minor ice hockey. He is a recipient of the [[Paul Loicq Award]] for his international work, and the Dr. [[Tom Pashby]] sports safety award for Canada.\n\n==Early life==\nAubry was born November 24, 1954, in [[Noranda, Quebec]],<ref name=\"IIHF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iihf.com/home-of-hockey/news/iihf-hof-2014/|title=Paul Loicq Award: Dr Mark Aubry (CAN)|date=2014|website=IIHF|access-date=July 31, 2018}}</ref> and learned to speak both English and French.<ref name=\"cpso\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cpso.on.ca/DoctorDetails/Aubry-Mark-John/0028044-32867|title=Aubry, Mark John (CPSO#: 32867)|website=[[College of Physicians and Surgeons of Ontario]]|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> He attended [[Merivale High School]], and played hockey, football and baseball at school.<ref name=\"MayorsCup\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insideottawavalley.com/community-story/3803201-fury-s-zito-picked-for-top-male-coach-award/|title=Fury's Zito picked for top male coach award|date=January 21, 2011|website=InsideOttawaValley.com|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> Aubry began playing [[junior ice hockey]] as a [[Centre (ice hockey)|centreman]]; he is listed at 6 feet tall, and 180 pounds, for the [[Rockland Nationals|Ottawa M and W Rangers]] in the [[Central Canada Hockey League]] during the 1971\u201372 season.<ref name=\"hockeydb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=72733|title=Mark Aubry hockey statistics and profile|website=hockeydb|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> During the 1972\u201373 season, he was coached by future [[IIHF Hall of Fame]] inductee, [[Derek Holmes (ice hockey)|Derek Holmes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/leagues/seasons/teams/0032181973.html|title=Ottawa M and W Rangers 1972&ndash;73 roster and scoring statistics|website=hockeydb.com|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref> Aubry won the most valuable player award and the sportsmanship award in the 1972\u201373 season with the Rangers, and won the sportsmanship award again in the 1973\u201374 season.<ref name=\"CCHL\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thecchl.ca/season-award-archives|title=Season Award Archives|website=Central Canada Hockey League|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> He then played for the [[Ottawa Gee-Gees]] during the 1974&ndash;75 and 1975&ndash;76 seasons,<ref name=\"hockeydb\" /><ref name=\"uottawa\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uottawa.ca/archives/sites/www.uottawa.ca.archives/files/hockey.pdf|title=Historique du hockey \u00e0 l'Universit\u00e9 d'Ottawa|language=french|website=University of Ottawa archives|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> while earning his medical degree.<ref name=\"dr-aubry\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hockeycanada.ca/en-ca/exclusive/quebec-hockey-summit/home/attendees/speakers/mark-aubry|title=Doctor Mark Aubry|website=Hockey Canada|access-date=July 31, 2018}}</ref> After playing, he worked as a trainer for the Gee-Gees.<ref name=\"MayorsCup\" />\n\n==Medical career==\nAubry graduated from the [[University of Ottawa]] in 1978.<ref name=\"cpso\" /> He established a [[family medicine]] office in [[Hull, Quebec]] on September, 18, 1981.<ref name=\"cpso\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> As of 2018, he is a director at the Ottawa Sport Medicine Centre,<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> and is a team physician for the [[Ottawa Senators]].<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/senators/team/front-office#medical-staff|title=Hockey Operations|website=Ottawa Senators|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> Aubry previously served as the team physician for the [[Ottawa 67's]] from 1996 to 2005,<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> the [[Ottawa Rough Riders]],<ref name=\"MayorsCup\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> the [[Ottawa Renegades]],<ref name=\"Renegades\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/opening-day-of-renegades-training-camp-highlighted-by-medicals-meetings-and-preparation/n-3168889|title=Opening day of Renegades training camp highlighted by medicals, meetings and preparation|date=May 28, 2005|website=OurSports Central|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> and the [[Ottawa Lynx]].<ref name=\"Pashby\" /> He was a trainer on [[minor ice hockey]] teams from 1989 to 2000, [[Chief Medical Officer]] (CMO) for the Canadian team at the [[1991 Winter Universiade]], and CMO of [[Canada at the 1992 Winter Olympics]] in [[Albertville]].<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" />\n\n===Sports medicine===\nAubry has spent significant time working in [[sports medicine]], lecturing on injury prevention, and researching [[concussion]]s and [[spinal cord]] injuries with respect to [[Checking (ice hockey)|body checking]] in ice hockey.<ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /><ref name=\"Pashby\" /><ref name=\"bodycheck\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeyeasternontario.ca/docs/HC_Body_Checking_Brief_1.pdf|title=Hockey Canada\u2014Body Checking Brief|date=April 17, 2013|website=Hockey Eastern Ontario|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He helped organize three symposiums on sports concussions (2001 in [[Vienna]], 2004 in [[Prague]], and 2008 in [[Z\u00fcrich]]), to assist doctors in identifying and treating concussions.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> Aubry was one of the physicians consulted for the 2011 report ''Brain Injury Guide for Youth'',<ref name=\"Kutcher\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ontarioshores.ca/UserFiles/Servers/Server_6/File/PDFs/bi_teen_guide_4.pdf|title=Brain Injury Guide for Youth|last=Kutcher|first=Stan|date=2011|page=3|website=Ontario Shores|publisher=Teenmentalhealth.org|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> and was one of the medical experts that helped write the module ''Making Head Way in Sport'' released in 2014, for the Coaching Association of Canada to educate on when it is okay to return to play.<ref name=\"CAC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.coach.ca/making-head-way-in-sport-elearning-module-is-now-available-at-no-charge-p156794|title=Making Head Way in Sport eLearning module is now available at no charge|date=July 17, 2014|website=Coaching Association of Canada|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> Aubry has also spoken against focusing too much on one sport at a young age, as it has not only \"taken the fun out of it\", but also has physical and cultural risks in not developing the person.<ref name=\"Scanlan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/ottawa-citizen/20170322/281479276237544|title=Can sports be fun again?|last=Scanlan|first=Wayne|date=March 22, 2017|website=PressReader.com|publisher=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|title=World Hockey Summit|quote=\"We\u2019re exposing these kids to an increased risk of injury at an age where I think we should still be talking about skill development and having fun.\"|source=&mdash;''Mark Aubry'', 2010<ref name=\"Fitz-Gerald\" /><ref name=\"TheHockeyNews\" /><ref name=\"sportsnet\" />|width=27.5%|align=right}}\n\nAt the 2010 World Hockey Summit, a joint project hosted by the National Hockey League, the [[National Hockey League Players' Association]], Hockey Canada, [[USA Hockey]], the IIHF, and the [[Canadian Hockey League]],<ref name=\"NHLPA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nhlpa.com/news/1-13651/whos-who-of-hockey-to-gather-for-world-hockey-summit|title=Who's Who of Hockey To Gather for World Hockey Summit|date=July 29, 2010|website=National Hockey League Players Association|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> Aubry called for raising the minimum age for body checking to 13 or 14 and eliminating hits from behind altogether.<ref name=\"Fitz-Gerald\" /><ref name=\"TheHockeyNews\" /> Based on his research and experience, he argued that children should be developing skills instead, as they are the most vulnerable to injury due to height and weight differences; he cited research which highlights risks of long-term effects for athletes who have had multiple concussions, specifically younger hockey players.<ref name=\"Fitz-Gerald\">{{cite news|title=Delay body checks till 13, 14, doc says|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|location=Winnipeg, Manitoba|last1=Fitz-Gerald|first1=Sean|last2=Strong|first2=Gregory|date=August 25, 2010|page=24|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-aug-25-2010-776136/}}{{free access}}</ref><ref name=\"TheHockeyNews\">{{cite web|url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/medical-doctor-nhl-coach-say-kids-shouldnt-learn-to-hit-until-later-teen-years|title=Medical doctor, NHL coach say kids shouldn\u2019t learn to hit until later teen years|date=August 24, 2010|website=TheHockeyNews|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"citizen\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/ottawa-citizen/20101107/282445640437138|title=HEADS-UP FOR HOCKEY: No agreement on how to fix concussions in youth sport|last=Scanlan|first=Wayne|date=November 7, 2010|via=PressReader|newspaper=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> Aubry called for instructing players that a body check is a way of separating an opponent from the puck, rather than continuing the perception of hockey as a rough sport where putting an opposing player through the boards is considered part of the game,<ref name=\"citizen\" /> given that no safety equipment could prevent serious injuries such as the [[Ronny Keller]] incident resulting in paraplegia.<ref name=\"B\u00e9land\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/sports/hockey/201303/07/01-4628664-un-joueur-suisse-paralyse-la-pire-blessure-au-hockey.php|title=Un joueur suisse paralys\u00e9: La pire blessure au hockey|language=French||last=B\u00e9land|first=Gabriel|date=March 7, 2013|website=La Presse|access-date=August 1, 2018}}</ref> Aubry has also testified before the [[Canadian International Trade Tribunal]] as an expert witness on the safety of hockey equipment.<ref name=\"CITT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.citt.gc.ca/en/file/1116/download%3Ftoken%3DvoNulTlm|title=Appeal No. AP-96-007|date=August 29, 1997|website=Canadian International Trade Tribunal|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAubry stated that awareness on the long-term effects of concussions increased partially because of the injuries to [[Sidney Crosby]], but noted that physicians in the [[National Hockey League]] still disagree on when players are healthy enough to return to play.<ref name=\"CMAJ\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cmaj.ca/content/cmaj/early/2011/12/19/cmaj.109-4080.full.pdf|title=Physicians must be brought up to speed on concussion risks|last=Fallis|first=Jordan|date=December 19, 2011|website=Canadian Medical Association Journal|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He was one of the authors in the 2017 report ''Can visible signs predict concussion diagnosis in the National Hockey League?''<ref name=\"BJSM\">{{cite web|url=https://bjsm.bmj.com/content/early/2017/04/04/bjsports-2016-097090.info|title=Can visible signs predict concussion diagnosis in the National Hockey League?|date=April 4, 2017|publisher=British Journal of Sports Medicine|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> He assessed Senators' player [[Clarke MacArthur]] for [[post-concussion syndrome]],<ref name=\"Clinton\">{{cite web|url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/senators-macarthur-will-need-to-pass-neuro-psych-test-in-order-to-play-again|title=Senators\u2019 MacArthur will need to pass \u2018neuro-psych test\u2019 in order to play again|last=Clinton|first=Jared|date=December 13, 2016|website=TheHockeyNews|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> and said that given MacArthur's history, it would be too risky to return to play.<ref name=\"Garrioch\">{{cite web|url=https://ottawasun.com/2017/01/20/ottawa-senators-decide-to-shut-down-clarke-macarthur-for-remainder-of-season/wcm/d1bc30e6-5496-4d2c-96a8-8245457c19c6|title=Ottawa Senators decide to shut down Clarke MacArthur for remainder of season|last=Garrioch|first=Bruce|date=January 20, 2017|website=Ottawa Sun|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> He also cited research that in-game concussion protocols need to be strictly adhered to, and reiterated the need to evaluate players at the first sign of possible concussion, rather than staying in the game.<ref name=\"Klein\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thespec.com/sports-story/4154849-researchers-call-for-safer-hockey-after-injuries-sideline-3-nhl-players-in-season-s-first-eight-days/|title=Researchers call for safer hockey after injuries sideline 3 NHL players in season\u2019s first eight days|last=Klein|first=Jeff Z.|date=October 12, 2013|website=Hamilton Spectator|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He recommends a proactive approach to ensure players do not return to play too soon, citing recent studies on the numbers of concussions in minor ice hockey, and specifically at the peewee age level when players are typically exposed to body checking for the first time.<ref name=\"sportsnet\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/hockey-summit/|title=Hockey Summit: Talk moves to injuries|date=August 24, 2010|website=Sportsnet.ca|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> He also spoke at the [[Canadian Academy of Sport and Exercise Medicine]] (CASEM) conference in August 2018, to address post-concussion syndrome, and methods for diagnosis.<ref name=\"CASEM\">{{cite web|url=https://casem-acmse.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/2018-Hockey-Preliminary-Program-FINAL5-4.pdf|title=Keep Your Edge|date=August 17, 2018|pages=2,4,6|website=Canadian Academy of Sport and Exercise Medicine|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===International hockey===\nAubry has served as the CMO of the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]] (IIHF) since 1998.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"Pashby\">{{cite web|url=http://www.drpashby.ca/2006/11/dr-mark-aubry-2006-dr-tom-pashby-sports-safety-award|title=Dr. Mark Aubry \u2013 2006 Dr. Tom Pashby Sports Safety Award|date=November 18, 2006|website=Dr. Pashby Sports Safety Fund|access-date=August 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814002052/http://www.drpashby.ca/2006/11/dr-mark-aubry-2006-dr-tom-pashby-sports-safety-award|archive-date=August 14, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> He took over the CMO position from [[Wolf-Dieter Montag]], who had served in the role since 1975.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gots.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/CV_Montag.pdf|title=Wolf-Dieter Montag \u2013 Curriculum Vitae|date=19 November 2014|website=Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Orthop\u00e4disch-Traumatologische Sportmedizin|language=de|page=2}}</ref> Aubry also sits on the medical commission of the [[International Olympic Committee]].<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> In this role, he advised against international travel to [[Beijing]] for the [[2003 Women's Ice Hockey World Championships]], which was ultimately cancelled because of the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS outbreak]].<ref name=\"SARS\">{{cite news|title=Women's hockey tourney canceled because of illness|newspaper=Colorado Springs Gazette|location=Colorado Springs, Colorado|date=March 31, 2003|page=64|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-mar-31-2003-776152/}}{{free access}}</ref> In [[ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics]], Aubry stated that the drug which [[Mattias \u00d6hlund|Mattias Ohlund]] tested positive for was contained in the medicine given to him after eye surgery, and should not be considered a doping infraction.<ref name=\"Lebrun\">{{cite news|title=Ohlund will play in Olympic games|newspaper=Medicine Hat News|location=Medicine Hat, Alberta|last=Lebrun|first=Pierre|author-link=Pierre LeBrun|date=January 22, 2002|page=10|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-jan-22-2002-776127/}}{{free access}}</ref> In [[ice hockey at the 2014 Winter Olympics]], Aubry stated that [[Nicklas B\u00e4ckstr\u00f6m|Nicklas Backstrom]]'s positive test for [[pseudoephedrine]] was a result of [[Cetirizine|Zyrtec-D]] taken to treat [[sinusitis]], and it should not be considered a doping infraction.<ref name=\"Carrera\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/olympics/nicklas-backstrom-fails-ioc-doping-test-misses-gold-medal-olympic-hockey-game/2014/02/23/fec67726-9cc0-11e3-8112-52fdf646027b_story.html|title=Nicklas Backstrom fails IOC doping test, misses gold medal Olympic hockey game|last1=Carrera|first1=Katie|last2=Sheinin|first2=Dave|date=February 23, 2014|website=Washington Post|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"TheLocal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.se/20140223/dreams-of-hockey-gold-sabotaged-by-ioc-sweden|title=Hockey star's doping ban 'was political'|date=February 23, 2014|website=The Local|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> Since Aubry became CMO, IIHF competitions and the Winter Olympic Games, ice hockey officials have been instructed to penalize all hits to the head, and are critiqued for any such missed calls.<ref name=\"citizen\" /> Aubry was one of the authors of the 2017 report ''Concussions in international ice hockey championships and olympic winter games between 2006 and 2015''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/320847926_Concussions_in_international_ice_hockey_championships_and_olympic_winter_games_between_2006_and_2015|title=Concussions in international ice hockey championships and olympic winter games between 2006 and 2015|date=June 2017|website=Researchgate|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> He later spoke at a CASEM conference, discussing how the faults in how the IIHF reports injuries, and the lessons to be learned.<ref name=\"CASEM\" />\n\n===Hockey Canada===\n{{quote box|title=Hockey Canada concussion seminar|quote=\"The fight in reducing concussions is global in nature and needs the help of every participant in the sport to prevent this injury through fair play, enforcement of the rules and other measures.\"|source=&mdash;''Mark Aubry'', 2010<ref name=\"Perry\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/hockey-canada-set-to-host-concussion-seminar-1.925991|title=Hockey Canada set to host concussion seminar|last=Perry|first=Rod|date=2010-11-09|website=CBC Sports|access-date=2018-08-04}}</ref>|width=27.5%|align=right}}\n\nAubry has served as the CMO of [[Hockey Canada]] since 2004,<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"Pashby\" /> assisted in developing the Hockey Canada Safety Program, and is a part the safety program committee.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" />  He pushed for Hockey Canada to adopt [[zero tolerance]] rules for hits to the head, whether accidental or not, and recommended that teams have seminars on the risks of concussions.<ref name=\"CMAJ\" /> Since he became CMO, Hockey Canada now requires team trainers to complete a course on handling concussions,<ref name=\"citizen\" /> recommends that players with concussions get a [[medical certificate]] with a doctor's permission to play,<ref name=\"CMAJ\" /> and standardized the graduated implementation of checking skills through its age levels across Canada.<ref name=\"bodycheck\" /> Aubry has also pushed for educating on ice officials for calling hitting from behind infractions, in addition to checks to the head.<ref name=\"B\u00e9land\" /> Aubry published [[Influenza A virus subtype H1N1|H1N1 influenza]] preventative guidelines prior to the 2009\u201310 hockey season,<ref name=\"H1N1\">{{cite news|title=H1N1 had an impact on teams' operations this season|newspaper=Portage La Prairie Central Plains Herald Leader|location=Portage La Prairie, Manitoba|date=February 27, 2010|page=44|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/sports-clipping-feb-27-2010-776138/}}{{free access}}</ref> and later issued guidelines for the use of water bottles and sports drinks, to prevent the spread of contagious viruses.<ref name=\"Mittelstaedt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/hockey-canada-shuns-sharing-of-bottles/article4291274/|title=Hockey Canada shuns sharing of bottles|last=Mittelstaedt|first=Martin|date=May 1, 2018|website=The Globe and Mail|access-date=August 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nAubry was given the Dr. [[Tom Pashby]] Sports Safety Fund Award in 2006, for his research on concussions and spinal cord injuries.<ref name=\"IIHF\" /><ref name=\"dr-aubry\" /> He received the Mayor's Cup in 2011, for outstanding contributions to sport in [[Ottawa]].<ref name=\"MayorsCup\" /> He was named the recipient of the [[Paul Loicq Award]] in 2014, for contributions to international ice hockey.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/dr-mark-aubry-will-receive-the-paul-loicq-award-for-contributions-to-hockey-through-research-on-spinal-injuries-and-concussions|title=Dr. Mark Aubry will receive the Paul Loicq Award for contributions to hockey through research on spinal injuries and concussions|date=April 22, 2014|website=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Paul Loicq Award}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aubry, Mark}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian physicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian physicians]]\n[[Category:Canada at the Winter Universiade]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey centres]]\n[[Category:Canadian sports physicians]]\n[[Category:Concussion activists]]\n[[Category:Hockey Canada personnel]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Quebec]]\n[[Category:International Ice Hockey Federation executives]]\n[[Category:Lecturers]]\n[[Category:Olympic team doctors]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Gee-Gees]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Lynx]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Renegades personnel]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Rough Riders personnel]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Senators executives]]\n[[Category:Paul Loicq Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Quebec]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rouyn-Noranda]]\n[[Category:University of Ottawa alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Flibirigit", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMedical career:wikilink event", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Aubry"}
{"title_page": "New York City Department of Transportation", "text_new": "{{Infobox government agency\n| agency_name     = Department of Transportation\n| type            = department\n| nativename      = \n| nativename_a    = \n| nativename_r    = \n| seal            = \n| seal_width      = \n| seal_caption    = \n| logo            = NYCDOT.svg\n| logo_width      = \n| logo_caption    = \n| picture         = \n| picture_width   = \n| picture_caption = \n| formed          = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} OR {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| preceding1      = \n| preceding2      = <!-- up to |preceding6= -->\n| dissolved       = \n| superseding     = \n| agency_type     =\n| jurisdiction    = [[New York City]]\n| headquarters    = [[55 Water Street]]<br/>[[Manhattan]], [[New York City|New York, NY]]\n| coordinates     = <!-- {{coord|LATITUDE|LONGITUDE|type:landmark_region:US|display=inline,title}} -->\n| motto           = \n| employees       = 5,060\n| budget          = $943.3 million\n| chief1_name     = [[Polly Trottenberg]]\n| chief1_position = Commissioner of Transportation\n| chief2_name     = \n| chief2_position = <!-- up to |chief9_name= -->\n| parent_department = \n| parent_agency   = \n| child1_agency   = \n| child2_agency   = <!-- up to |child25_agency= -->\n| keydocument1    = [[New York City Charter]]\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.nyc.gov/dot}}\n| map             = \n| map_width       = \n| map_caption     = \n| footnotes       = \n| embed           =\n}}\n\nThe '''New York City Department of Transportation''' ('''NYCDOT''') is the agency of the [[government of New York City]]<ref>[[New York City Charter]] \u00a7 2901; \"There shall be a department of transportation, the head of which shall be the commissioner of transportation.\"</ref> responsible for the management of much of [[New York City]]'s transportation infrastructure. [[Polly Trottenberg]] is the current Commissioner of the Department of Transportation, and was appointed by Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] on January 1, 2014.\n\n==Overview==\nThe Department of Transportation's responsibilities include day-to-day maintenance of the city's streets, highways, bridges and sidewalks. The Department of Transportation is also responsible for installing and maintaining the city's street signs, traffic signals and street lights. DOT supervises street resurfacing, pothole repair, parking meter installation and maintenance, and the management of municipal parking facilities. DOT also operates the [[Staten Island Ferry]]. DOT is the exclusive provider of day-to-day operations and maintenance on New York State-maintained roads and highways in city limits, while major repairs and capital improvements on state-owned roads are performed by the State DOT. Both DOT and [[NYSDOT]] reserve the right to install signage, signals, and other roadway features on state highways, which then become maintained on a daily basis by DOT. DOT sets the speed limit on all roads and highways in the city, including those owned by NYSDOT.\n\nDOT is also responsible for oversight of transportation-related issues, such as authorizing jitney van services and permits for street construction. DOT also advocates for transportation safety issues, including promotion of pedestrian and [[bicycle safety]].\n\nIts regulations are compiled in title 34 of the ''[[New York City Rules]]''.\n\n==Organization==\n[[File:NYC DOT fleet of Prius 07 2010 9641.JPG|thumb|alt=DOT fleet of Toyota Prius hybrid electric vehicles|DOT fleet of [[Toyota Prius]] [[hybrid electric vehicle|hybrids]]]]\n[[File:USA-NYC-Staten Island Ferry.JPG|thumb|alt=Staten Island Ferry|[[Staten Island Ferry]] ]]\n[[File:28-11 QPN DoE DoT jeh.jpg|thumb|alt=The DOT's traffic light control center in Queens|28-11 [[Queens Plaza (Queens)|Queens Plaza]] North, where the DOT's traffic light control center is housed]]\n*Commissioner of Transportation\n**First Deputy Commissioner\n***Sidewalk Inspection and Management\n***Staten Island Ferry Service\n***Bridges\n***Transportation Planning & Management\n***Roadway Repair and Maintenance\n***Information Technology and Telecommunications\n***Borough Commissioners\n****Brooklyn Borough Commissioner\n****Manhattan Borough Commissioner\n****Bronx Borough Commissioner\n****Queens Borough Commissioner\n****Staten Island Borough Commissioner\n**Policy\n**External Affairs\n**Finance, Contracting, and Program Management\n**Human Resources and Facilities Management\n**Legal\n\n==Management and budget==\nAs of 2017, DOT had the budget and staff as follows:<ref>[http://www.nyc.gov/html/omb/downloads/pdf/erc6-16.pdf FY 2017 City Budget], page 334E, New York City Office of Management and Budget</ref>\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n!Division\n!Number of Employees\n!Budget (millions)\n|-\n|Executive\n|598\n|$116.8 \n|-\n|Highway Operations\n|1492\n|$277.8\n|-\n|Transit Operations\n|694\n|$91.8\n|-\n|Traffic Operations\n|1418\n|$353.3\n|-\n|Bureau of Bridges\n|858\n|$106.3\n|-\n|'''Total'''\n|'''5060'''\n|'''$943.3'''\n|}\n\n==Bridges==\nThe DOT operates 794 roadway and pedestrian bridges throughout New York City, including 25 movable bridges.<ref name=bridge-report>{{cite book|title=Annual Bridge and Tunnel Condition Report 2011|year=2011|publisher=NYC DOT|location=New York City|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/html/bridges/annualbridgereport.shtml}}</ref> The agency's portfolio includes most of the [[East River]] and [[Harlem River]] bridges, as well as smaller bridges throughout the city. DOT operates two [[retractable bridge]]s (the Borden Avenue and Carroll Street bridges). Other agencies that operate road bridges in New York include the [[MTA Bridges and Tunnels|MTA]], the [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]] and the [[New York State Department of Transportation|New York State DOT]].\n\n{{col-begin}}{{col-break}}\n'''[[East River]] bridges:'''\n*[[Brooklyn Bridge]]                                             \n*[[Manhattan Bridge]]                                          \n*[[Williamsburg Bridge]]                                  \n*[[Queensboro Bridge]]                                       \n*[[Roosevelt Island Bridge]]\n*[[Wards Island Bridge]]\n{{col-break|gap=4em}}\n'''[[Harlem River]] bridges:'''\n*[[Willis Avenue Bridge]]\n*[[Third Avenue Bridge (New York City)|Third Avenue Bridge]]\n*[[Madison Avenue Bridge]]\n*[[145th Street Bridge]]\n*[[Macombs Dam Bridge]]\n*[[Washington Bridge]]\n*[[University Heights Bridge]]\n*[[Broadway Bridge (Manhattan)|Broadway Bridge]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Incidents==\nAt approximately 1:30 a.m. on May 24, 2012, DOT employee Harry Robinson ran over and killed Roxana Buta while operating a DOT truck.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2013/05/12/nyc-employee-gets-off-scot-free-after-hit-and-run-truck-kills-21-year-old-beauty/|title=NYC employee gets off scot free after hit-and-run truck kills 21-year-old beauty|author=|date=12 May 2013|website=nypost.com|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[New York City Office of Administrative Trials and Hearings]] (OATH), for hearings conducted on summonses for quality of life violations issued by the Department\n* [[New York State Department of Transportation]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2014}}\n\n== External links==\n{{commonscat|New York City Department of Transportation }}\n*{{Official website}}\n* [http://rules.cityofnewyork.us/codified-rules?agency=DOT Department of Transportation] in the [[Rules of the City of New York]]\n* [https://nyctmc.org NYC DOT Real Time Traffic Information]\n\n{{Transportation in New York City|state=autocollapse}}\n{{NYC Bridge}}\n{{New York City Government}}\n\n[[Category:Government departments of New York City|Transportation]]\n[[Category:Transportation in New York City|Department of Transportation]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox government agency\n| agency_name     = Department of Transportation\n| type            = department\n| nativename      = \n| nativename_a    = \n| nativename_r    = \n| seal            = \n| seal_width      = \n| seal_caption    = \n| logo            = NYCDOT.svg\n| logo_width      = \n| logo_caption    = \n| picture         = \n| picture_width   = \n| picture_caption = \n| formed          = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} OR {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| preceding1      = \n| preceding2      = <!-- up to |preceding6= -->\n| dissolved       = \n| superseding     = \n| agency_type     =\n| jurisdiction    = [[New York City]]\n| headquarters    = [[55 Water Street]]<br/>[[Manhattan]], [[New York City|New York, NY]]\n| coordinates     = <!-- {{coord|LATITUDE|LONGITUDE|type:landmark_region:US|display=inline,title}} -->\n| motto           = \n| employees       = 5,060\n| budget          = $943.3 million\n| chief1_name     = [[Polly Trottenberg]]\n| chief1_position = Commissioner of Transportation\n| chief2_name     = \n| chief2_position = <!-- up to |chief9_name= -->\n| parent_department = \n| parent_agency   = \n| child1_agency   = \n| child2_agency   = <!-- up to |child25_agency= -->\n| keydocument1    = [[New York City Charter]]\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.nyc.gov/dot}}\n| map             = \n| map_width       = \n| map_caption     = \n| footnotes       = \n| embed           =\n}}\n\nThe '''New York City Department of Transportation''' ('''NYCDOT''') is the agency of the [[government of New York City]]<ref>[[New York City Charter]] \u00a7 2901; \"There shall be a department of transportation, the head of which shall be the commissioner of transportation.\"</ref> responsible for the management of much of [[New York City]]'s transportation infrastructure. [[Polly Trottenberg]] is the current Commissioner of the Department of Transportation, and was appointed by Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] on January 1, 2014.\n\n==Overview==\nThe Department of Transportation's responsibilities include day-to-day maintenance of the city's streets, highways, bridges and sidewalks. The Department of Transportation is also responsible for installing and maintaining the city's street signs, traffic signals and street lights. DOT supervises street resurfacing, pothole repair, parking meter installation and maintenance, and the management of municipal parking facilities. DOT also operates the [[Staten Island Ferry]]. DOT is the exclusive provider of day-to-day operations and maintenance on New York State-maintained roads and highways in city limits, while major repairs and capital improvements on state-owned roads are performed by the State DOT. Both DOT and [[NYSDOT]] reserve the right to install signage, signals, and other roadway features on state highways, which then become maintained on a daily basis by DOT. DOT sets the speed limit on all roads and highways in the city, including those owned by NYSDOT.\n\nDOT is also responsible for oversight of transportation-related issues, such as authorizing jitney van services and permits for street construction. DOT also advocates for transportation safety issues, including promotion of pedestrian and [[bicycle safety]].\n\nIts regulations are compiled in title 34 of the ''[[New York City Rules]]''.\n\n==Organization==\n[[File:NYC DOT fleet of Prius 07 2010 9641.JPG|thumb|alt=DOT fleet of Toyota Prius hybrid electric vehicles|DOT fleet of [[Toyota Prius]] [[hybrid electric vehicle|hybrids]]]]\n[[File:USA-NYC-Staten Island Ferry.JPG|thumb|alt=Staten Island Ferry|[[Staten Island Ferry]] ]]\n[[File:28-11 QPN DoE DoT jeh.jpg|thumb|alt=The DOT's traffic light control center in Queens|28-11 [[Queens Plaza (Queens)|Queens Plaza]] North, where the DOT's traffic light control center is housed]]\n*Commissioner of Transportation\n**First Deputy Commissioner\n***Sidewalk Inspection and Management\n***Staten Island Ferry Service\n***Bridges\n***Transportation Planning & Management\n***Roadway Repair and Maintenance\n***Information Technology and Telecommunications\n*